<!-- Async WordPress.com Remote Login -->
<script id="wpcom_remote_login_js">
var wpcom_remote_login_extra_auth = '';
function wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( element_id ) {
	var dom_node = document.getElementById( element_id );
	if ( dom_node ) { dom_node.remove(); }
}
function wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_classes( class_name ) {
	var dom_nodes = document.querySelectorAll( '.' + class_name );
	for ( var i = 0; i < dom_nodes.length; i++ ) {
		dom_nodes[i].remove();
	}
}
function wpcom_remote_login_final_cleanup() {
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_classes( "wpcom_remote_login_msg" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_key" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_validate" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_js" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_request_access_iframe" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_request_access_styles" );
}

// Watch for messages back from the remote login
window.addEventListener( "message", function( e ) {
	if ( e.origin === "https://r-login.wordpress.com" ) {
		var data = {};
		try {
			data = JSON.parse( e.data );
		} catch( e ) {
			wpcom_remote_login_final_cleanup();
			return;
		}

		if ( data.msg === 'LOGIN' ) {
			// Clean up the login check iframe
			wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_key" );

			var id_regex = new RegExp( /^[0-9]+$/ );
			var token_regex = new RegExp( /^.*|.*|.*$/ );
			if (
				token_regex.test( data.token )
				&& id_regex.test( data.wpcomid )
			) {
				// We have everything we need to ask for a login
				var script = document.createElement( "script" );
				script.setAttribute( "id", "wpcom_remote_login_validate" );
				script.src = '/remote-login.php?wpcom_remote_login=validate'
					+ '&wpcomid=' + data.wpcomid
					+ '&token=' + encodeURIComponent( data.token )
					+ '&host=' + window.location.protocol
						+ '//' + window.location.hostname;
				document.body.appendChild( script );
			}

			return;
		}

		// Safari ITP, not logged in, so redirect
		if ( data.msg === 'LOGIN-REDIRECT' ) {
			window.location = 'https://wordpress.com/log-in?redirect_to=' + window.location.href;
			return;
		}

		// Safari ITP, storage access failed, remove the request
		if ( data.msg === 'LOGIN-REMOVE' ) {
			var css_zap = 'html { -webkit-transition: margin-top 1s; transition: margin-top 1s; } /* 9001 */ html { margin-top: 0 !important; } * html body { margin-top: 0 !important; } @media screen and ( max-width: 782px ) { html { margin-top: 0 !important; } * html body { margin-top: 0 !important; } }';
			var style_zap = document.createElement( 'style' );
			style_zap.type = 'text/css';
			style_zap.appendChild( document.createTextNode( css_zap ) );
			document.body.appendChild( style_zap );

			var e = document.getElementById( 'wpcom_request_access_iframe' );
			e.parentNode.removeChild( e );

			document.cookie = 'wordpress_com_login_access=denied; path=/; max-age=31536000';

			return;
		}

		// Safari ITP
		if ( data.msg === 'REQUEST_ACCESS' ) {
			console.log( 'request access: safari' );

			// Check ITP iframe enable/disable knob
			if ( wpcom_remote_login_extra_auth !== 'safari_itp_iframe' ) {
				return;
			}

			// If we are in a "private window" there is no ITP.
			var private_window = false;
			try {
				var opendb = window.openDatabase( null, null, null, null );
			} catch( e ) {
				private_window = true;
			}

			if ( private_window ) {
				console.log( 'private window' );
				return;
			}

			var iframe = document.createElement( 'iframe' );
			iframe.id = 'wpcom_request_access_iframe';
			iframe.setAttribute( 'scrolling', 'no' );
			iframe.setAttribute( 'sandbox', 'allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation' );
			iframe.src = 'https://r-login.wordpress.com/remote-login.php?wpcom_remote_login=request_access&origin=' + encodeURIComponent( data.origin ) + '&wpcomid=' + encodeURIComponent( data.wpcomid );

			var css = 'html { -webkit-transition: margin-top 1s; transition: margin-top 1s; } /* 9001 */ html { margin-top: 46px !important; } * html body { margin-top: 46px !important; } @media screen and ( max-width: 660px ) { html { margin-top: 71px !important; } * html body { margin-top: 71px !important; } #wpcom_request_access_iframe { display: block; height: 71px !important; } } #wpcom_request_access_iframe { border: 0px; height: 46px; position: fixed; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; min-width: 100%; z-index: 99999; background: #23282d; } ';

			var style = document.createElement( 'style' );
			style.type = 'text/css';
			style.id = 'wpcom_request_access_styles';
			style.appendChild( document.createTextNode( css ) );
			document.body.appendChild( style );

			document.body.appendChild( iframe );
		}

		if ( data.msg === 'DONE' ) {
			wpcom_remote_login_final_cleanup();
		}
	}
}, false );

// Inject the remote login iframe after the page has had a chance to load
// more critical resources
window.addEventListener( "DOMContentLoaded", function( e ) {
	var iframe = document.createElement( "iframe" );
	iframe.style.display = "none";
	iframe.setAttribute( "scrolling", "no" );
	iframe.setAttribute( "id", "wpcom_remote_login_key" );
	iframe.src = "https://r-login.wordpress.com/remote-login.php"
		+ "?wpcom_remote_login=key"
		+ "&origin=aHR0cHM6Ly9ibGFja2xpc3RkZWNsYXNzaWZpZWQubmV0"
		+ "&wpcomid=9473618"
		+ "&time=1603821720";
	document.body.appendChild( iframe );
}, false );
</script>

		function addLoadEvent(func) {
			var oldonload = window.onload;
			if (typeof window.onload != 'function') {
				window.onload = func;
			} else {
				window.onload = function () {
					oldonload();
					func();
				}
			}
		}

<h3>‚≠ï Script 5:2 Greyson Blaise (‚Ññ 37)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief:</b> Red has been having a blast, relaxing poolside, collecting colorful new associates and pursuing the occasional criminal to keep Cooper happy. He and Liz are hitting it off as a father/daughter act. Aram and Samar are now a couple. Ressler is in debt to fixer Henry Prescott for helping him hide his involvement in Laurel Hitchin‚Äôs death. Tom has returned from his adventures and holds the key to Red and Liz‚Äôs future relationship ‚Äì a suitcase full of bones, left to him at the suicide of Mr Kaplan ‚Äì a suitcase Red is desperate to recover.

<b>Red:</b> Go there. Get a room under the name Mr. DeLacey. Say it!<br />
Security Officer: Mr. DeLacey.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Right. I&#8217;ll make contact when it&#8217;s safe. Until then, talk to no one. Do you understand? Good luck, mate, and Godspeed!</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red and Liz get in Red‚Äôs car ]<br />
Liz: [ CHUCKLES ] Is that really a Picasso in the back seat?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes. That was a nice surprise.<br />
[ ENGINE STARTS, REVS ] [ TIRES SCREECH ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Back in DC ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Harold, you&#8217;re obviously upset.<br />
Cooper: No, I&#8217;m not upset. &#8220;Upset&#8221; is an emotional word. My reaction isn&#8217;t about emotion. It&#8217;s about my job. It&#8217;s about you consistently keeping me in the dark and refusing to respect my role as the head of this task force. And you know what else it&#8217;s about? Your ego and your obvious failure to understand that this entire operation, everything we&#8217;re trying to do here, is hanging by a thread!<br />
<b>Red:</b> My mistake. I thought you might be upset.<br />
Cooper: You lured us in, acted like the only thing you needed from us was a ride to that auction. The next thing I know, my people are stealing paintings‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> To be fair, stealing back a painting. Or trying, at least.<br />
Cooper: Not to mention half-a-dozen invoices for a party at a house on Lake Como!<br />
<b>Red:</b> Right. Please don&#8217;t forget to pay the catering bill. Those folks were very, very nice.<br />
Cooper: After all of that, what do we have to show for it? Nothing. You handed Blaise over to the Italian police, so we don&#8217;t even get credit for the arrest.<br />
<b>Red:</b> True, the Italians will get credit for arresting Blaise with &#8220;The Sea of Galilee.&#8221; Of course, it&#8217;s not &#8220;The Sea of Galilee,&#8221; which they will undoubtedly realize shortly, at which point they will be forced to release Blaise with apologies.<br />
Cooper: So nobody gets him.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Wrong. You get him, Harold. You and this Task Force.<br />
[ Red gives Cooper the Napoleon necklace ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Because while the Carabinieri have bogus evidence, you have the genuine article. Fast, hard proof of Blaise&#8217;s criminal activities all over the globe. Art heists, missing masterpieces. That necklace alone should be enough to put him away and get your new Director off your back for a long weekend, at least.<br />
Cooper: What was in that house that was so important? </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ At the motel, Red and Liz are poolside. Liz plays with the Lincoln penny ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Penny for your thoughts.<br />
Liz: Why&#8217;d you do it?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Why&#8217;d you let me? It wasn&#8217;t the wine.<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m scared of you. Now more than ever. Of who you are, because you might be who I am, too. I let you do it because it felt like the right thing to do. It wasn&#8217;t. But it certainly felt that way because‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> Because you&#8217;re my daughter?<br />
Liz: In more ways than I care to admit.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ DOOR CREAKS ] [ Tom enter warily. A man is tied to a chair and gagged. He has been badly beaten, but is conscious ]<br />
Tom: Are you Dennison? Who did this to you?<br />
[ Tom pulls down the gag ]<br />
Dennison: [ COUGHS ]<br />
Tom: What happened? You okay? Who did this to you?<br />
[ ELEVATOR BELL DINGS ] [ ELEVATOR DOORS SLIDE OPEN ]<br />
[ Tom pulls Dennison‚Äôs gag back up ]<br />
Tom: I&#8217;m sorry.<br />
[ Tom goes into the closet, pulling shut the louvered doors ]<br />
[ DOOR CREAKS ] [ Red and Dembe enter ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Albert? Albert, look at me. Do you know who I am?<br />
[ Dennison nods ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> You&#8217;re a tough son of a bitch. Your loyalty to Kate is admirable. But you will die, Albert here and now, if you don&#8217;t tell me where that suitcase is. Who has it? I won&#8217;t ask you again.<br />
Dennson: [ LAUGHS ] [ CRYING ]<br />
[ Red shoots Dennison in the chest üí•üí•üí• ]<br />
[ DOOR CREAKS ]<br />
[ After Red and Dembe leave, Tom comes out, pulls down Dennison‚Äôs gag ]<br />
Dennison: [ GRUNTS ]<br />
Tom: Hey, hey. Who‚Äì Why did I pick up the suitcase?<br />
Dennison: Ole‚Äì<br />
Tom: What?!<br />
Dennison: Oleander. Find him.<br />
Tom: Who&#8217;s Oleander? Who is he? What is‚Äì What is Oleander?<br />
[ Dennison loses consciousness ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Tom is home cooking ] [ CELLPHONE RINGING ] [ CELLPHONE BEEPS ]<br />
Nik: Hey, it&#8217;s me.<br />
Tom: Nik, what&#8217;s up?<br />
Nik: I&#8217;ve been thinking about this, what you said. I have no interest in getting involved with Reddington, but if what you said If you think Liz is in some kind of danger, just tell me what you need me to do, okay?<br />
Tom: Thank you. Nik, that&#8217;s, uh‚Äì Thanks. Look, I don&#8217;t feel comfortable talking on the phone.<br />
Can we meet?<br />
Nik: Yeah. Text me an address.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Tom is at home, cooking ] [ Liz enters, wearing a little red dress ]<br />
Liz: Wow, smells amazing!<br />
Tom: Yeah, well, hold your judgment until you&#8217;ve tried it, because I might end up killing us all. [ CHUCKLES ]<br />
Liz: &#8220;Us all&#8221;? What&#8217;s going on?<br />
[ DOORBELL RINGS ] [ Liz runs to the door and opens it ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Elizabeth, good evening.<br />
[ Red hands Liz a bottle of Champagne ]<br />
Liz: Hello! What&#8217;s going on?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Tom didn&#8217;t tell you? I was invited to dinner.<br />
Tom: I set four place settings. Every time I see you, you&#8217;re with Dembe, so I just thought the two of you, you know. I don&#8217;t know what I thought.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Thank you, Tom. I regret I can&#8217;t stay. I have another engagement. Sorry to have inconvenienced you, but at least you&#8217;ll have plenty of leftovers. Before I go, let&#8217;s have a toast.<br />
[ Tom opens the bottle of Champagne and pours it ]<br />
Liz: What exactly are we celebrating?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Tom&#8217;s return, of course! Your family must be very happy to have you back. I remember warning you not to embark on that silly adventure. But nothing ventured, nothing gained. Welcome home.<br />
Tom: Cheers.<br />
[ They sip ]<br />
Tom: So, what have you been up to? [ Smiles ]<br />
[ Liz glances sideways at Red. Red smiles awkwardly ]</p>

<h2>üî¥ Script: 5:3 Miss Rebecca Thrall (‚Ññ 76)</h2>

<h3>‚≠ï Script 5:3 Miss Rebecca Thrall (‚Ññ 76)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief:</b> Red has been winning, then losing, then winning Cooper over again with his madcap approach to restoring his empire. Liz has decidedly mixed feelings, having enjoyed the fun of taking down Greyson Blaise while knowing it was crazy and wrong. Tom, in the meantime, has witnessed a murder in which Red‚Äôs ruthlessness was evident ‚Äì ruthlessness that it certain to be visited on Tom if Red finds out he is the one in possession of the mysterious suitcase containing a skeleton.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Two policemen break down the door of Scottie Stansbury‚Äôs apartment ]<br />
Officer McGinnis: Baltimore PD. Come out, Stansbury. We got a warrant.<br />
Officer Parker: We know you&#8217;re here, Scottie. Why don&#8217;t you come on out, make this easier?<br />
[ The two officers separate. McGinnis comes upon Scottie Stansbury in the kitchen, at the sink.  Scottie turns around ]<br />
Scottie: Ah, please. I-If you take me in and my parole officer finds out I&#8217;ve been using‚Äì<br />
[ Officer McGinnis is training his gun directly at Stansbury ]<br />
Scottie: W- what&#8217;s going on?<br />
McGinnis: I&#8217;m sorry, Scottie.<br />
[ üí•üí• ] [ Blood splatters. Scottie falls ]<br />
Officer Parker: [ From elsewhere in the apartment ] McGinnis!<br />
[ McGinnis goes over to Scottie, who lies motionless, fires üí•üí• two shots from a different gun he has brought, toward the entry to the kitchen, then places the gun in Scottie‚Äôs hand ]<br />
[ Officer Parker appears ]<br />
Parker: McGinnis! What the hell happened?<br />
McGinnis: I-I just‚Äì He drew. He fired. Is he‚Äì<br />
[ Parker feels for a pulse ]<br />
Parker: He&#8217;s dead. You came in‚Äì What? You had no choice. You had to fire, right?<br />
McGinnis He had a gun. Yeah, I had to fire.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Police chief: McGinnis. Hey. Can you hear me?<br />
McGinnis: Yes. Chief, look, I got nothing to hide. I&#8217;ll wave my Garrity rights. I-I was following protocol.<br />
Chief: And I&#8217;m sure IA will confirm that, but right now, I want you to go home and call a lawyer. You need a lawyer.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A woman in red shoes with spike heels walks ]<br />
[ Car door opens ] [ Car door closes ]<br />
[ The woman gets in the car with Officer McGinnis, hands him a slip of paper ]<br />
McGinnis: You sure nobody followed you?<br />
Miss Rebecca Thrall: Password to the account. Funds are now available.<br />
McGinnis: [ Sighs ] I didn&#8217;t think it&#8217;d be this bad.<br />
Thrall: You&#8217;re alive, Officer McGinnis. Which is more than we can say for Scottie Stansbury. You&#8217;ve done your job. Now let me do mine.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red is at the Terrace Vista Motor Lodge where he has been staying. He is dressed in a fleece robe with a hoodie, baseball cap, t-shirt and shorts, trying to get ice out of the ice machine. One ice cube drops out. He bangs the machine and shakes it fruitlessly, then heads back toward his room. He sees the door has been broken open. He turns around ]<br />
[ Red knocks on the door of another room ] [ A perky young woman with a Southern accent answers ]<br />
Piper: What&#8217;s up, buttercup? You finally change your mind, decide to join me and Gary tonight in the hot tub?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yeah. Uh, tonight? Maybe.<br />
Piper: Is it the scab on his leg?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Oh, no, no, no! No, no, no! Gary&#8217;s ‚Äì Gary. I&#8217;m just distracted. I locked myself out of my room. I certainly don&#8217;t want to go down to the lobby. I was hoping I might use your phone.<br />
Piper: Oh, yes, of course, silly. Get in here.<br />
[ Both chuckle ]<br />
Piper: You coming to social hour tonight? Gonna bring Daddy&#8217;s favorite little pickle-bites.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Piper, I have no idea what that means.<br />
Piper: I spread cream cheese on a slice of dried beef, wrap it up real good around a dill. Put a little toothpick in &#8217;em, real good.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ On Piper‚Äôs phone ] Dariush! It&#8217;s Bruno. I&#8217;m sorry. I- I somehow locked myself out of my room.<br />
[ The windows of the motor lodge look down on the central court with the pool. Red sees three thuggish-looking men, including one in a cowboy hat, walking around the pool ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I was hoping‚Äì Oh right. No. Oh, no, that&#8217;s fine. That would be gre‚Äì Wait. [ Chuckling ] I found it now! Never mind. I- Yeah, right here, in my pocket of all places. [ Chuckles ] Okay. I&#8217;m sorry. Thank you.<br />
[ Red hangs up ]<br />
Piper: I&#8217;ll tell Gary we&#8217;ll hot tub at 8:00.<br />
[ Opens Door ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Don&#8217;t forget the pickle-bites.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red returns to his room, enters cautiously. On the mirror in the bathroom is written in soap ‚ÄúRIVERA WANTS YOU‚Äù ]<br />
[ Cellphone beeps, dialing ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Dembe. Yeah. Did you get a plate number? Okay.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Tom and Nik (Liz‚Äôs ex-boyfriend who is an ER MD) sit on a bench next to a medical or academic building ]<br />
Tom: Who is this guy anyways? I mean, what kind of &#8220;medical expert&#8221; agrees to help covertly identify human remains?<br />
Nik: I&#8217;m sorry. I didn&#8217;t realize he needed a r√©sum√© and a urine sample to get the job. You asked me for help, I&#8217;m getting you help, and I&#8217;m breaking the law in the process.<br />
Tom: Yeah, for Liz.<br />
Nik: Right. For Liz. That worked out well last time.<br />
Tom: He&#8217;s a friend of yours, this Pete?<br />
Nik: He has access to the kinds of medical equipment you need.<br />
[ A thin, scruffy-looking guy comes out of the building ]<br />
Tom: That guy? Did he even go to medical school?<br />
Nik: He was the smartest kid at Harvard during my residency. Then he sort of dropped out. Today he&#8217;s plugged in to some kind of network of criminal drug activities. You two should get along swimmingly.<br />
Pete: What up, Nikky? [ Sniffles ] You got gray as Grandma. You must be ‚Äì<br />
Tom: Tom.<br />
Pete: Cool fake name. You a cop?<br />
Tom: All right, you know what? Forget it.<br />
Nik: This isn&#8217;t a joke, Pete.<br />
Pete: Yeah, well, I don&#8217;t know your friend.<br />
[ Talking over each other: ]<br />
Tom: You know what? It&#8217;s my mistake‚Äì<br />

And he tells the poor man that if he presses the button, an old man in Mongolia drops dead. Now, he won&#8217;t tell him why, only that his death is good for the people. So he pushes the button, takes the money, and goes home. But he&#8217;s haunted by what he did. He can&#8217;t spend any of the money, and eventually, he commits suicide. A man recently told me that story. <h3>‚≠ï Script 5:5 Ilyas Surkov (‚Ññ 54)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief: </b> Nik Korpal, Liz‚Äôs ex-boyfriend, friend of both Liz and Tom, and erstwhile MD-on-call for Red ‚Äì is dead. Nik and Tom had secretly been trying to ID the bones sent via Tom by Mr Kaplan for Liz (the existence of which Liz remains unaware) with help from Pete McGee, a genius medical technician with shady connections to the drug underworld. Red is desperate to recover the bones and doesn‚Äôt know where they are. Pete used Liz‚Äôs FBI ID which Tom got from Liz (again, without her knowledge) to gain access to the government‚Äôs CODIS database to ID the bones ‚Äì then he went silent. At Tom‚Äôs behest, Nik paid a visit to Pete‚Äôs apartment where he was jumped from behind and strangled. Whoever killed Nik left with the suitcase full of bones. Meanwhile, Red is beginning to rebuild an empire of sorts, starting with a network of safe houses based on the Post Office‚Äôs mail ‚Äúhold‚Äù lists.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ In front of a brick house in Leeds, England, children are selling lemonade ]<br />
Father: We never pass by a lemonade stand without stopping first. Isn&#8217;t that right, Christian?<br />
Christian: Never.<br />
Father: Thank you.<br />
Ethan: Would you like a straw?<br />
Father: Uh, yes, please.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

Kim: What? Honey, it&#8217;s‚Äì<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 5:6 The Travel Agency (‚Ññ 90)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief:</b> To find out who killed Nik Korpal, Liz has turned to Red while Tom has located Pete McGee‚Äôs girlfriend. Red has purchased a non-profit dog grooming service to use for money laundering. Red has also obtained the evidence file for Nik. It contained the key to the missing suitcase of bones that both Tom and Red are independently trying to recover ‚Äì as well as Nik‚Äôs cellphone. The last message on Nik‚Äôs phone was a request to call someone back. When Red called the number, Tom answered. Stunned, Red hung up without saying a word.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ It is morning at the Dawson household ]</p>

</p></blockquote>

Brokaw on TV: At the Berlin Wall at the Brandenburg Gate, I&#8217;m Tom Brokaw. Brandenburg Gate, of course, is in East Berlin, and the sound that you hear and what you&#8217;re seeing tonight ‚Äì not hammers and sickles, but hammers and chisels, as young people take down this wall bit by bit. Earlier this evening, the Communist Central Committee in East Berlin
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Calvin and Eleanor Dawson are in the kitchen, drinking coffee and working a crossword puzzle ]<br />
Calvin Dawson: End of an era, huh?<br />

are singing and dancing. Reunited right on top

Soldiers dismantling it, not guarding it with rifles.
</p></blockquote>

[ Calvin goes to PO Box 342 and removes an envelope, pulls out a red folder. It contains a dossier ]</p>

Calvin shoots him. üí•üí•üí• Knobbs throws his axe at Calvin, but it misses and gets stuck in a tree. Calvin pulls the axe out of the tree. Calvin shoots again üí• ]<br />

[ Calvin raises the axe and strikes ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red is playing miniature golf. Liz walks up ]<br />
Liz: Ooh, can I play?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Uh! You&#8217;re in my line of sight.<br />
Liz: Oh, there&#8217;s a hole under the lighthouse.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m playing the carom.<br />
Liz: Ah.<br />
<b>Red:</b> That&#8217;s it. Dembe and I have scheduled a tournament. It&#8217;s been in the works for some time, but we couldn&#8217;t quite settle on a format. I finally unearthed the Peoria System with a double-par limit, and here we are. The tournament is this week. And I have every intention of winning.<br />
[ Red putts. The ball misses wildly ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Oh!<br />
Liz: And here I thought all old, rich, white men were good at golf.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Maybe it&#8217;s my putter. Mitchell Dunning of Dupont Circle is about to be assassinated.<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m sorry ‚Äì Mitchell who?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Dunning. He found me through an associate of mine and is looking to disappear. My problem is that I don&#8217;t have the resources to help him at present. Yours is that Mr Dunning believes the hit was contracted through The Travel Agency.<br />
Liz: A travel agency?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Not <i>a</i> travel agency, Elizabeth. <i>The</i> Travel Agency ‚Äì a murder-for-hire ring that lived in the shadows for nearly 30 years. Their assassins carried out a variety of contract hits until they mysteriously closed their doors 12 years ago, dashing any hope that law enforcement might one day solve the rash of killings the Agency left in their wake.<br />
Liz:  So if this Dunning guy is right and they are after him‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> Innocents and not-so-innocents have targets on their backs, beginning with Mitchell Dunning.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Post Office ]<br />
Liz: The Travel Agency was a consortium of anonymous killers responsible for a variety of unsolved murders ‚Äì the assassination of a civil-rights activist in 1983, the poisoning of an anti-Glasnost Soviet businessman in &#8217;87.<br />

Aram: Mitchell David Dunning. Lives in Dupont Circle and imports high-end furniture. Offices in Paris, London, and New York.<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />

Ressler: Of course.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ KNOCK ON DOOR ] [ A man looks out the peephole ]<br />

Cooper: Isaiah Hill.<br />
Man: Never heard of him.<br />

Cooper: Where&#8217;d he go?<br />
Man: We still unofficial?<br />
Cooper: Only if you give me a straight answer. Isaiah Hill ‚Äì where is he? </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Mrs Dunning: You packed the laptop, right?<br />
Mitchell Dunning: I told you yes. Along with the phone and the chargers. What&#8217;d your sister say?<br />
Mrs Dunning: Cabin&#8217;s empty. Garage code is the address backwards.<br />
Mitchell Dunning: Here you finish the bags. I&#8217;m gonna set the alarm.<br />
Samar: Mitchell Dunning? FBI agents Navabi and Keen.<br />
Mitchell Dunning: FBI? I don&#8217;t‚Äì What&#8217;s going on?<br />

Mitchell Dunning: What threat? There can&#8217;t‚Äì You must have me confused with someone else.<br />

Liz: It&#8217;s Wednesday.<br />
Mitchell Dunning: Look, officers, I appreciate your concern, but clearly, you&#8217;ve got the wrong guy. There&#8217;s no threat. I&#8217;m a salesman. I import‚Äì<br />
[ Mitchell Dunning is shot üí•üí• ] [ A gun retracts from the trunk of a dated Oldsmobile ]<br />
[ ENGINE STARTS ] [ The car speeds off ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ POLICE RADIO CHATTER, SIREN WAILING ]<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m sorry to be asking you these questions now, but if we&#8217;re gonna find whoever did this, we need to know everything you know.<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
Samar: Liz, you have to see this. I found it in the car.<br />
[ Newspaper headline reads ‚ÄúBrutal Axe Murder in York County‚Äù about the murder of Edward Knobbs ]<br />

Mrs Dunning: No. Why? Who is he? </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Tom leaves a courthouse marked ‚ÄúRecords Division‚Äù carrying a yellow envelope. Dembe is standing outside. Tom sees him, realizes he has no choice, and gets into Red‚Äôs car ]<br />
Tom: [ CHUCKLES ] Are you following me now?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Mr. Kaplan gave you a suitcase. In it was a skeleton she never should have unearthed and whose identity must remain secret.<br />
Tom: I don&#8217;t know what you&#8217;re talking about.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I understand the temptation acting on a fine woman&#8217;s dying wish.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ DOOR OPENS at Lena Mercer‚Äôs apartment. Crespin enters ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
<b>Red:</b> But your quest has cost Nik Korpal his life, and persisting will put whomever you involve in harm&#8217;s way.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Crespin: I prefer no one gets hurt.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Tom: Secrets put people in harm&#8217;s way. Keeping them in the dark ‚Äì a talent you and I share. Or shared. I&#8217;m out of that business. And if I have a quest, it&#8217;s to shine a light on the darkness you create to help Liz find her way out of the enormous shadow you cast.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You asked Nik to identify the bones, and he was killed for his trouble by someone who knows their identity and, therefore, their value. That killer is likely searching for a way to contact me since, knowing their value, he knows they are most valuable to me. I will allow myself to be found, recover the suitcase, eliminate the man for his troubles, and rebury the body in a place where it will be lost to the sands of time, as originally intended.<br />
Tom: Whatever secret you&#8217;re hiding from Liz ‚Äì it&#8217;ll come out. Family secrets always do.<br />
<b>Red:</b> What&#8217;s in the envelope?<br />
Tom: [ Leaving ] What envelope?<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Crespin: You are to stop looking for Pete McGee. You are to act as if Pete McGee never existed. Say it.<br />
Lena: Is he doing this? Did he send you?<br />
Crespin: Say it, Lena.<br />
Lena: Pete McGee doesn&#8217;t exist.<br />
Crespin: Keep it that way. Or I&#8217;ll be back.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Landry Knobbs: I don&#8217;t understand. You think this man who was killed was looking into my father&#8217;s murder? Did they know each other?<br />
Samar: We were hoping that you might be able to answer that.<br />
Landry: Mitchell Dunning ‚Äì I don&#8217;t think I&#8217;ve ever seen him.<br />
Liz: Were you and your father close?<br />
Landry: We were. After Mom passed, I used to come out here every week, help out around the house.<br />
Liz:: Did he ever come to visit you?<br />
Landry: In the city? God, no. I don&#8217;t think Dad ever left the state after he closed the Agency.<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m sorry ‚Äì the Agency?<br />
Landry: The Seawall Travel Agency. Dad owned it for years.<br />
Samar: Landry, do you know if your father happened to keep any of his old work records?</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz and Samar go through the old files from The Seawall Travel Agency ]<br />
Samar: Knobbs traveled the world with his family.<br />
Liz: And orchestrated hits. Check this out.<br />
[ Liz shows Samar a long list of names ]<br />

[ A single headstone marks the gravesite of the two girls ~ ‚ÄúSisters Here &amp; Hereafter.‚Äù They were 2 and 3 years old when they died ]<br />
Calvin: [ VOICE BREAKING ] No.<br />
Eleanor: We were in Miami on what I thought was a family vacation. I collapsed at the pool. My appendix burst. Do you remember? When I went into surgery, you took the girls out of the hospital. You told me you didn&#8217;t want them to be scared. But what you didn&#8217;t tell me was that you had somewhere to be that afternoon. A job.<br />
Calvin: El- Eleanor? [ Voice Breaking ] Not my girls.<br />
Eleanor: You took our girls with you to kill a man. You left them in the car and walked inside the back of a restaurant to do a job which should&#8217;ve taken you ‚Äì what, two minutes? But it didn&#8217;t take you two minutes, Calvin. Because the man you went to kill knew you were coming ‚Äì got a jump on you, left you for dead, bleeding and beaten in the alley while our girls were locked in the car too young to know any better. The medical examiner said electrolyte abnormalities kicked in and sparked cardiac arrhythmias and something he called &#8220;skin slippage.&#8221; Everyone from Seawall is dead. Except Wright. The police got to him. But everyone else. It doesn&#8217;t bring the girls back or make me feel as good as I thought it would ‚Äì but you did it.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ SIRENS WAILING ] [ Liz and Samar and other agents arrive at the cemetery. Eleanor draws a gun and trains it on Calvin ]<br />
Liz: Eleanor Dawson! FBI! I need you to put that gun down!<br />
Eleanor: They told me you were at the convalescent home looking for him. You know who he is, right?<br />
Liz: Yes. If you put your gun down, we can talk about it. I want to talk about it.<br />
Eleanor: I don&#8217;t know what you people think is gonna happen. You don&#8217;t gain anything by arresting me or putting me in jail. I&#8217;m not a danger to society, like he is!<br />
Liz: My name is Elizabeth. I&#8217;m a mother, like you. I want to understand.<br />
Eleanor: You&#8217;re a mother?<br />
Liz: Yes.<br />
Eleanor: Oh, good. Then you&#8217;ll understand this.<br />
[ Eleanor shootsüí•üí•Calvin. An FBI sharpshooter takes out Eleanorüí•]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Isaiah Hill: That&#8217;s it. That&#8217;s my statement about what I saw. What comes next?<br />
Cooper: The US attorney will review what you said, decide whether to file charges. And if it goes to court, you&#8217;ll be called to testify.<br />
Isaiah: In court? Against Wilson? Where everyone can see?<br />
Cooper: Nothing will happen if you do. You have my word on that.<br />
Isaiah: The word of a cop?<br />
Cooper: A cop who knows what you&#8217;re going through. My father marched for Dr. King. He was attacked by police dogs in Birmingham, was beaten on Bloody Sunday. For his troubles, the Bureau opened up a secret file on him, called him a radical, enemy of the state. He was my hero, and the organization I&#8217;ve devoted my life to did everything in its power to destroy him. But that&#8217;s why I devoted my life to it ‚Äì to make sure that the Bureau never did to another black man what it did to my old man.<br />
Isaiah: And mine.<br />
Cooper: Come on. I&#8217;ll take you home.<br />
Isaiah: I need some help, Mr. Cooper. I&#8217;m gonna try. [ VOICE BREAKING ] But I think I need some help. [ VOICE BREAKING ]<br />
Cooper: Yeah. Let&#8217;s get you home, Isaiah.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Lena: Did you find what you were looking for?<br />
Tom: Nope. But I did find this.<br />
Lena: [ Reads ] &#8220;Congratulations, Lena Mercer. You have qualified to receive a UVA Visa card.&#8221; I don&#8217;t understand.<br />
Tom: You have Pete&#8217;s passwords. He has yours. And he&#8217;s using them to open new credit cards in your name. The reason we can&#8217;t find Pete is he&#8217;s not using his accounts. He&#8217;s using yours. And that&#8217;s how we&#8217;re gonna find him.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Crespin is watching Tom and Lena from a distance ]<br />
Crespin: [ On phone ] The warning didn&#8217;t take. Yes, sir. I&#8217;ll make sure of it next time.<br />
[ CELLPHONE BEEPS ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Harrison Storm&#8217;s ‚ô™ &#8220;Change It All&#8221; plays ]<br />
[ At the miniature golf course ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I feel like you&#8217;re a natural golfer, and I&#8217;m just not.<br />
Dembe: You&#8217;re naturally good at many things.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Like what? Like what? </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Take it from me
</p></blockquote>
<p>Dembe: [ Pause ] You&#8217;re good company.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ LAUGHING ] Well, that doesn&#8217;t count! </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ All of what I know
</p></blockquote>
<p>Dembe: I&#8217;ll think of something.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You know what? Never mind.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz reflects in the cemetery by the headstone of the two Dawson girls, now splashed with the blood of their parents ]</p>
<blockquote><p>

</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />

[ Liz grabs a form from the counter ]<br />
Liz: Will you?<br />
Tom: [ CHUCKLING ] What?<br />
Liz: I know it&#8217;s super spur-of-the-moment, and this is not very romantic. I mean, we&#8217;re under fluorescent lights. These pens are attached to the table, for God&#8217;s sake, but‚Äì Look. With everything I see in a day, I just feel so lucky to have you. And if we don&#8217;t do this now‚Äì<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script: 5:7 The Kilgannon Corporation (‚Ññ 48)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief: </b> Red has confronted Tom about the suitcase full of bones left for Liz by Mr Kaplan. Tom has denied any knowledge, even as he works with Pete McGee‚Äôs former girlfriend Lena to locate Pete in the belief Pete killed Nik Korpal and has the suitcase. Tom has researched Pete‚Äôs shady past and has evidence that Pete has stolen Lena‚Äôs identity and is getting credit cards in her name. Lena has obtained a copy of Pete‚Äôs computer files from his office, which may contain information on the identity of the bones. Liz and Tom have finally gone to the courthouse and are, at last, remarried.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A couple and their two young children are at the beach ] [ BIRDS CALLING ]<br />
Mother: Did they go all the way down to Arctic Avenue?<br />
Father: [ On cellphone ] Yeah, if you hit Arctic, you went too far. No, turn back. Yeah, you&#8217;re gonna hang a left on Ashley Street. All right, I&#8217;ll see you in a bit. [ Throws football to son ] All right, Brax. Bring it on! Whoo! There you go!<br />
[ WAVES CRASHING ] [ The daughter finds a sand dollar, then sees a body washed up on the beach. She looks out. There are bodies floating, plus a few survivors swimming or struggling ashore ]<br />
Girl: Mom?<br />
[ Survivor coughing ]<br />
Girl: Mom!<br />
Mother: Michael! Come on. Come on.<br />
Father: Yeah, I see them. Come on. Brax, Poppy, go to your mother! Come on. Come on, Brax. Go! Go! Go! Go! Go!<br />
[ ALL COUGHING ] [ The father begins to help survivors ashore ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ CELLPHONE VIBRATING ]<br />
Tom: If you answer your phone‚Äì<br />
Liz: Ohh.<br />
Tom: ‚Äìwe are getting a divorce.<br />
Liz: I have to meet Reddington in 30 minutes.<br />
Tom: No! No, you don&#8217;t! Just tell him you&#8217;re on your honeymoon. Tell him that your second husband insists you take one day off.<br />
Liz: Um, technically‚Äì<br />
Tom: One day.<br />
Liz: ‚Äì you are my first husband because our first marriage was annulled‚Äì<br />
Tom: Uh-huh.<br />
Liz: ‚Äìand last night was our first time‚Äì<br />
Tom: Mm-hmm.<br />
Liz: ‚Äìsleeping together as husband and wife.<br />
Tom: Hmm.<br />
Liz: Well, actually, like, the third time‚Äì Well, first night.<br />
Tom: Mm. Mm-hmm.<br />
Liz: And morning.<br />
Tom: Mm-hmm.<br />
[ LAUGHS ] [ CELLPHONE RINGING ]<br />
Tom: Guy really has a problem.<br />
Liz: That&#8217;s your phone.<br />
Tom: Oh.<br />
Liz: &#8220;No Caller ID&#8221;? That&#8217;s very mysterious.<br />
[ CELLPHONE BEEPS ]<br />
Tom: I want to keep it that way.<br />
[ Tom tosses phone ] [ CELLPHONE THUMPS LIGHTLY ]<br />
Liz: Hey, you could&#8217;ve won a set of steak knives or the lottery.<br />
Tom: You know what? I did win the lottery when you agreed to marry me‚Äì<br />
Liz: Aww.<br />
Tom: ‚Äìagain.<br />
Liz: And I have steak knives.<br />
Tom: So we&#8217;re good.<br />
Liz: It&#8217;s fine. Don&#8217;t need to answer.<br />
Tom: Ah.<br />
[ LAUGHS ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ BIRDS CHIRPING ] [ Red is seated at an outdoor table when Liz arrives ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Are you okay?<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m better than okay. I&#8217;m great. We&#8217;re great ‚Äì Tom and I. We got married. See? [ Shows diamond ] Now&#8217;s normally when people say &#8220;congratulations.&#8221;<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ CHUCKLES ] [ Getting up ] Sorry. Tom and I have had our differences, but I believe he wants what&#8217;s best for you. And Agnes. Congratulations, Elizabeth.<br />
[ They hug ]<br />
Liz: Thank you.  You know, um‚Äì for the first time in a very long time, I feel‚Äì I don&#8217;t know‚Äì [ INHALES DEEPLY ] Happy. [ CHUCKLES ]<br />
[ They sit ] [ Liz picks up the newspaper Red was reading ]<br />
Liz: Then I see what&#8217;s going on in the world.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Migrants hidden away in a Chinese freighter bound for South Carolina.<br />
Liz: Human trafficking.<br />
<b>Red:</b> &#8220;Trafficking&#8221; implies the passengers are being moved against their will. These people paid for the privilege. All over the world, criminals are smuggling people into countries they can&#8217;t enter legally. Some are hoping for a better life. Others are escaping war or persecution for a price. People like me can help them.<br />
Liz: Like you? You&#8217;re in the human-smuggling business?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I was. My organization provided access to the Americas, various European countries, select destinations in Asia. For a fair price, I provided a quality service. Mr Kaplan put an end to that. In her feverish desire to destroy me, Kate destroyed my relocation networks.<br />
Liz: Why are you telling me this?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Because, as you can see, a ruthless and unscrupulous player has stepped forward to fill the void left by my absence. The ship these people were packed into like sardines was a death trap. It wasn&#8217;t fit to make the journey, which is why it sank two miles off the Carolina coast.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ DOOR OPENS ] [ Colin Kilgannon sits at a table. His father, Arthur, stands next to him. Two men enter with a Chinese man ]<br />
Colin Kilgannon: [ IRISH ACCENT ] Mr. Zhang I&#8217;m a simple man. When I hire a mechanic [ CHUCKLES ] I expect him to know how to fix my car. When I hire a Snakehead, I expect him to know how to ship our clients without killing them.<br />
Zhang: It was a mistake. Please.<br />
Colin: 29 clients died. Clients who were supposed to pay a balance upon arrival. But that&#8217;s obviously not gonna happen now that they&#8217;re dead.<br />
Zhang: We did what you said. We put a-as many people on‚Äì<br />
[ GUNSHOTS. üí•üí• ] [ THUDS ] [ SHELLS CLATTERING ]<br />
Colin: Sorry, Da. I wish you didn&#8217;t have to see that.<br />
Arthur Kilgannon: Dead clients don&#8217;t make us money. But neither do dead employees.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<b>Red:</b> Elizabeth, whomever has filled the vacuum left by my downfall has to be stopped, or more innocent people will die.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Ressler: So, Reddington was moving people illegally across borders. Do I have that right?<br />
Liz: In his mind, he was giving people hope.<br />
Aram: Yeah. Some are only alive because he got them away from, you know, whatever they were running from.<br />
Samar: Don&#8217;t assume that all those people were good people. Most, perhaps, but border control is essential.<br />
Liz: Whatever you believe about the business, bottom line, people are dying, and that needs to stop.<br />
Ressler: The player who took over Reddington&#8217;s routes ‚Äì He doesn&#8217;t know who it is?<br />
Liz: Which is why he needs our help.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Cooper: Sounds to me like what you want is help getting rid of the competition.<br />
<b>Red:</b> There are much easier ways to earn a dollar than moving migrants. I did it because someone will, and if it&#8217;s going to be done, it should be done well by someone who holds to certain standards.<br />
Cooper: Very noble. A man in your position has the luxury of acting on his own conscience. I am the Assistant Director of the FBI. I&#8217;ll help you take down whoever took your place, but the Bureau can&#8217;t be responsible for putting you back in the global smuggling business.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Fair enough.<br />
Cooper: Good. Then where do we start?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Greece. The route north, through Macedonia. It&#8217;s the most traveled and the most lucrative. It&#8217;s a simple plan. We put someone in the pipeline. He gets the name of the person who took over my routes. We pull him out.<br />
Cooper: Does that mean you know the access point they&#8217;re using?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I do. Normally, I&#8217;d suggest we insert one of your people to get the name, but this time I suggest we use one of mine.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Aram: We&#8217;ll stay in touch via this device I can embed in your rear molar. It works like a microphone and allows me to pick up your voice.<br />
Dembe: And I can hear you because the same transmitter allows the sound of your voice to travel up the jawbone and into my inner ear.<br />
Aram: Yeah, that&#8217;s- that&#8217;s right. Um, how&#8217;d you know that?<br />
Dembe: <a href="https://www.khanacademy.org">Khan Academy</a>. I took their course in electrical engineering.<br />
Aram: Uh, don&#8217;t you also speak, like, five languages?<br />
Dembe: Eight.<br />
Aram: You know, other than the fact that you sometimes have to kill people for a living, you&#8217;re, like, my role model. Open up.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Thessaloniki, Greece ]<br />
[ Ressler, Samar and Liz are on-site in a vehicle ] Dembe walks some distance away ]<br />
[ MAN SPEAKING NATIVE LANGUAGE IN DISTANCE ]<br />
[ DOORBELL CHIMES ] [ Dembe enters shop ]<br />
Ressler: He&#8217;s in. Aram, you have ears?<br />
Aram: I do. We are up and live.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ At the Post Office ]<br />
Cooper: Okay, heads up, people. We have no idea what we&#8217;re walking into here.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Samar: Aside from the fact that we have no legal authority in Greece and we&#8217;re sending a civilian in undercover.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Aram: He&#8217;s gonna crush it.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Clerk: Welcome, friend. Help you find something?<br />
Dembe: I was told you have a copy of Eratosthenes&#8217; map of the world.<br />
Clerk: It&#8217;s not for sale.<br />
[ Dembe plops a bundle of bills on the counter ]<br />
Dembe: I was also told everything&#8217;s for sale.<br />
Clerk: You&#8217;ll have to ask the boss.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The clerk leads Dembe to another room ]<br />
[ DOOR CREAKS ] [ DOOR CLOSES ]<br />
[ MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY ON TV ] [ SIREN WAILING ON TV ] [ SOUND ON TV MUTES ]<br />
[ REMOTE THUMPS LIGHTLY ]<br />
Cornelius Goga: Let me look at you. What&#8217;s your name?<br />
Dembe: Malik Charef.<br />
Goga: Where you from, Malik Charef?<br />
Dembe: Oran.<br />
Goga: I see. And how does an Algerian find himself so far from home?<br />
Dembe: I traveled to Zawiyah, bought passage across the water to Lesbos. And now I&#8217;m seeking safe transport to Berlin.<br />
Goga: Search him.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Liz: He&#8217;s onto something. He&#8217;s checking for a wire.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Goga: Who are you? The police? The Astynomia? Open your mouth. Open.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Ressler: Sir, what do you want us to do?<br />
Cooper: Hold. Let it play out.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Goga: You&#8217;re not from Oran. You&#8217;ve had dental work done in the West. Maybe I should kill you. [ STERNLY ] Who are you?<br />
Dembe: Count down from five. If I&#8217;m with the police, they&#8217;re listening. They won&#8217;t let you get to zero. They&#8217;ll storm this place, and then you won&#8217;t have to guess who I am.<br />

[ Budron continues pounding on the wall of the truck ] [ GRUNTING ]<br />
[ Dembe takes the metal bar ]<br />
Dembe: It&#8217;s not working. We need to save the air we have. You need to slow your breathing.<br />
Budron: Give me that!<br />
[ WOMAN COUGHS LIGHTLY ] [ Budron and Dembe sit ]<br />
Budron: [ In Arabic, to man next to him ] You know what else could save air? Fewer people.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Liz: This just came in from Reddington. Those are the drivers who received the burn signal.<br />
Ressler: I don&#8217;t understand. How did Reddington‚Äì<br />
Liz: He got to Kilgannon, got the payroll records. We have their legal names and addresses and the routes they were assigned.<br />
Samar: They&#8217;ve found three trucks so far ‚Äì two in a forest, one in a parking garage. There&#8217;s no sign of Dembe.<br />
Liz: How much time do we have left?<br />
Samar: About 35 minutes.<br />
Ressler: All right, we need to get to these guys and find those trucks before they turn up full of bodies. Wait. There were seven trucks. There&#8217;s only six on this list.<br />
Liz: Reddington is going after Dembe&#8217;s driver.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red forces his way into the driver‚Äôs house ] [ GUN COCKS ] [ He goes through the house. There is no one home ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Budron: We all don&#8217;t have to die.<br />
Dembe: Sit down.<br />
Budron: No. Look. If there is something we can do, something to give a few of us more time to be saved‚Äì<br />
Older Woman: What are you saying?<br />
Budron: I&#8217;m sorry, but if there were fewer people, there would be more air for the others.<br />
Dembe: Enough.<br />
Older Man: Let him talk. Who do you propose?<br />
Budron: I was thinking by age. The oldest first‚Äì That seems fair.<br />
Older man: Fair? To murder my wife?<br />
Budron: Yes. To save others.<br />
Dembe: [ Standing up ] And who will do this? You? Look her in the eye as you choke off her last breath?<br />
Budron: I am not going to die here!<br />
Dembe: And you will not kill anyone either.<br />
Budron: I don&#8217;t remember anybody putting you in charge. Maybe you will go first.<br />
[ Budron tries to hit Dembe. Dembe slugs him ‚ö°Ô∏èknocking him down ] [ GRUNTS ]<br />
Dembe: [ SIGHS ] Even with fewer people, the air won&#8217;t last long. We will not start killing each other just to die anyway. Whatever happens we do it together.<br />
[ Dembe sits down again by Ana who is hyperventilating ] [ Dembe lifts Ana‚Äôs hand to her heart ]<br />
Dembe: Can you feel that? Can you hear it? That&#8217;s your heartbeat. Concentrate on it. Slow it down. It&#8217;s okay. Shh.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<b>Red:</b> Driver&#8217;s not here. I&#8217;m too late.<br />
Liz: You don&#8217;t know that. All of his stuff his clothes, prescription bottles ‚Äì It&#8217;s all still there, right?<br />
<b>Red:</b> He knows the police are after him.<br />
Liz: He can&#8217;t run with nothing. He has to come back.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You ever wonder why Dembe stays with me why anyone so decent would spend his days at the side of someone so indecent?<br />
Liz: You saved him. He owes you his life. He protects you because you protected him.<br />
<b>Red:</b> No, Elizabeth. Dembe didn&#8217;t stay with me because he saw me as his savior. He stayed with me because he saw me for the man I really was ‚Äì a man surrounded by darkness. No friends who could be trusted, no faith that loyalty or love could ever truly exist. I was‚Äì Well, I was younger then. Angrier. Dembe connected his life with mine to show me, that day and every day, that the world is not what I fear it to be. He is the light in the darkness. Living proof that there is another way, that life can be good, that people can be kind, that a man like me might one day dream of becoming a man like him. He pledged his life, offered it up as evidence that I was wrong about this world. Dembe guards my life because he&#8217;s determined to save my soul.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Budron: You were wrong. Nobody knows we&#8217;re here. Nobody&#8217;s coming.<br />
Dembe: [ To Ana ] It&#8217;s okay.<br />
[ BOTH BREATHING HEAVILY ]<br />
Dembe: Sleep. Your parents will be waiting when you wake up.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red‚Äôs CELLPHONE BEEPS ] [ FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING ] [ LOCK DISENGAGES ] [ DOOR CREAKS ]<br />
[ The truck driver enters ] [ GUN COCKS ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> The truck. Where is it? </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red rolls open the door of Dembe‚Äôs truck. The migrants begin to crawl out. Dembe has Ana, who is unconscious ]<br />
Dembe: She barely has a pulse.<br />
[ BRAKES SQUEAL ]<br />
Liz: The ambulances are on their way.<br />
Dembe: She won&#8217;t make it if we wait for an ambulance.<br />
[ Dembe carries Ana to Red‚Äôs car. They get in and Red starts the engine ]<br />
[ TIRES SCREECH ] [ ENGINE REVS ]<br />
[ Samar, Liz and Ressler help the other migrants out of the truck ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Dembe comes out of the hospital, gets in the car with Red ]<br />
Dembe: [ SIGHS ] She&#8217;s alive. And sleeping. The doctors expect a full recovery.<br />
<b>Red:</b> The resilience of the young.<br />
[ ENGINE STARTS ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I thought I&#8217;d lost you.<br />
Dembe: Not yet, old friend.<br />
<b>Red:</b> The world can be such an unsparingly savage place. One could be forgiven for believing that evil will triumph in the end.<br />
Dembe: Those who believe so are wrong.<br />
<b>Red:</b> If you&#8217;d died today, like that, it would be all the proof I needed that you are the one who is wrong.<br />
Dembe: And here I am.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ CHUCKLES ] And here you are.<br />
&nbsp;<br />
Samar: They found all seven trucks, packed full of people. The police say some might not make it, but we saved a lot of lives today.<br />
Liz: So that they could be arrested and deported like the others at the warehouse. What about them?<br />
Samar: Ressler is on with Cooper now.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Ressler: [ On phone ] 15 passengers as expected, yeah. Three were taken to the hospital by ambulance. And Dembe and Reddington took the girl.<br />
Cooper: So you have 10 there.<br />
Ressler: Correct. Police have their hands full with the warehouse and the other trucks. And once everyone&#8217;s been cleared by medical, they asked us to transport everyone we&#8217;ve got back to the station house. Sir, look, I have to say, I-I knew this was happening. I knew people were risking their lives by the hundreds of thousands. But, I mean, knowing it and seeing it‚Äì<br />
Cooper: It&#8217;s different. Agent Ressler, stay on the line.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ DIALING ] [ CELLPHONE RINGS, BEEPS ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Harold! I&#8217;m here with Dembe.<br />
Cooper: Dembe. Thank God.<br />
[ Cross Record&#8217;s ‚ô™ &#8220;High Rise&#8221; plays ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Oh, we have some good news. It seems the young Ana Elazar will live to see a brighter day.<br />
Cooper: Another day, maybe. I&#8217;m not so sure about brighter. Her parents were arrested. Who knows how long it&#8217;ll take to reunite them? And even then, her future is back at that migrant camp in Greece.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Bleak business, Harold.<br />
Cooper: Yes, as we speak, my agents are preparing to transport 10 recovered migrants into the custody of the Macedonian police. 10 people with only minutes left, perhaps, before they wind up back in a cell. </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ I watch the sun<br />

</p></blockquote>
<p>Of course, were my agents to encounter any resistance while making the trip to the local station house, our hands would be tied. We have no formal authority in Macedonia. In fact, we&#8217;ve been specifically ordered not to engage with hostiles of any kind.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Ressler‚Äôs van transporting the migrants encounters Red‚Äôs car blocking the road, Red and Dembe standing next to it ]<br />

<b>Red:</b> Donald!<br />
[ Ressler smirks ]</p>

</p></blockquote>

<p>[ DOOR OPENS ]<br />
Garvey: You know, all this time I&#8217;ve given you to think has prompted me to do some thinking of my own. And, uh‚Äì I got to tell you, I&#8217;m stumped. When you consider all the people on the planet who would be interested in the contents of that case and you multiply that number by an even greater number of unspeakable things those people would do to get it, how the hell could it end up in the hands of a little pissant like you?<br />
Tom: Maybe because I&#8217;m not the pissant you think I am.<br />
Garvey: Oh, no? Do tell.<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 5:8 Ian Garvey (‚Ññ 13)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief: </b> Tom has been taken hostage by a sinister man (Ian Garvey) and has promised to lead him to Red to save his own life, after Garvey ruthlessly killed both Lena Mercer and Pete McGee when they proved useless to him in helping him get to Red. Garvey now has the mysterious suitcase full of bones. Crespin, the man who was following Lena (who it turns out was working for Red all along), has reported this news to Red ‚Äì to Red‚Äôs genuine alarm. Liz still knows not a thing about the existence of the suitcase left for her by Mr Kaplan to reveal a dark secret of Red‚Äôs, or of the fact that it had anything to do with Nik‚Äôs death ‚Äì not to mention anything of the game of cat-and-mouse Tom and Red have been playing as Tom has tried to determine the identity of the skeleton the suitcase contains, which Red has warned Tom must remain forever a secret.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz steps off the elevator at the Post Office ]<br />
Liz: [ On phone ] I&#8217;m sure you&#8217;re fine and I&#8217;m overreacting. And you just can&#8217;t answer your phone, because for some reason that we&#8217;ll both be laughing about this time tomorrow, but something is wrong. And something‚Äì<br />
Recording: If you&#8217;re satisfied with your message, please press 1.<br />
Cooper: What is it?<br />
Recording: If you would like to record‚Äì<br />
Liz: Tom. He&#8217;s missing.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Tom is still bound at the barn where he is being held. The bodies of Lena Mercer and Pete McGee are next to him. He crawls over to Lena and sees a chain with a thin metal pendant she is wearing. He reaches to remove the pendant ]<br />
Tom: I&#8217;m sorry.<br />
[ Tom closes Lena‚Äôs eyes ]<br />
[ DOOR OPENS ] [ Ian Garvey enters ]<br />
Tom: She didn&#8217;t even know anything. Neither did he.<br />
Garvey: He had the bones. She was looking for them. They knew enough. The question is, what you know. Reddington sent you after the suitcase. Did he tell you why?<br />
Tom: He didn&#8217;t tell me anything.<br />
Garvey: No, I don&#8217;t think he did. The last thing he&#8217;d want is for you to ID these bones. But you couldn&#8217;t resist, could you, Tom? So you and your friends ran a DNA search through CODIS. Thank you for that, by the way. Curiosity killed these cats, but for me, it&#8217;s a gift that&#8217;s gonna keep on giving. Whatever you imagine the answer might be, it&#8217;s better than that. Reddington&#8217;s power is legendary. With this, I control that power. You&#8217;re going to set up a meeting between us so I can tell him the good news. But in case you&#8217;ve had a change of heart‚Äì<br />
[ Switch snaps, MACHINE WHIRRING ]<br />
[ Men load Lena‚Äôs body into a chute. It is emulsified, gore splashing against against a vinyl screen and splattering onto Tom ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red‚Äôs man Crespin is positioned some distance from the barn, looking through binoculars. He is on the phone with Red who is in his Mercedes as Dembe drives ]<br />
Crespin: Yeah, I have eyes.<br />
<b>Red:</b> How many?<br />
Crespin: Uh. Five hostiles, maybe more.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Tom and the others?<br />
Crespin: Status unknown. But‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> But what?<br />
Crespin: Raymond. It&#8217;s not good.<br />
<b>Red:</b> We&#8217;re 20 minutes away. I want an update in 10.<br />
[ CELLPHONE BEEPS ]<br />
Dembe: We should have backup.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Too many people know about this situation already. This needs to end now.<br />
[ CELLPHONE RINGS ] [ CELLPHONE BEEPS ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes?<br />
Tom: It&#8217;s me. I did what you hired me to do. I got the package.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Any problems?<br />
Tom: Nope. Piece of cake.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Where are you now?<br />
Tom: Motel in Stone Ridge, 546 Roscoe Lane, Room 16.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I can be there in half-an-hour.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Garvey: You three with me. The rest, deal with him.<br />
[ Bobby Navarro, Garvey‚Äôs lead henchman, holds up a large yellow envelope ]<br />
Navarro: Hey, what about this?<br />
Garvey: That stays. The last thing I want is that thing anywhere near Reddington.<br />
[ Navarro puts the envelope inside the suitcase with the bones ]<br />
Tom: I did what you asked, now let me go.<br />
[ Garvey slugs‚ö°Ô∏èTom, knocking him off his chair ]<br />
Garvey: Plastic stays, too. Any trouble, he joins his pals.<br />
[ Garvey leaves ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Recording: Hey, it&#8217;s Tom. Leave a message. I will call you back. [ BEEP ]<br />
Liz: Me again. And again and again.<br />
Recording: This mailbox is full and cannot accept messages at this time.<br />
Samar: We issued a BOLO. Sent a message to every field office.<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m sorry to put you guys through this. I&#8217;m sure I&#8217;m overreacting.<br />
Samar: Don&#8217;t take this the wrong way, but are you sure you know everything Tom is up to?<br />
Liz: I thought I did. I don&#8217;t know.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ CELLPHONE BEEPS ] [ CELLPHONE RINGING ]<br />
Liz: Reddington, anything?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I just spoke to you 20 minutes ago.<br />
Liz: You said you had a lead.<br />
<b>Red:</b> On Nik Korpal&#8217;s death.<br />
Liz: But you think the two are related?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Elizabeth, I&#8217;m doing what I can. I&#8217;m sure Harold is, as well.<br />
Liz: I know. I&#8217;m trying to convince myself everything&#8217;s fine, but I&#8217;m doing a terrible job.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Tom is capable of getting himself both into and out of trouble. If he&#8217;s in harm&#8217;s way, I am quite certain he&#8217;s put in motion an escape plan, about which the people holding him are completely unaware.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Tom relocates the small metal pendant among the gore ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Liz: But who would be holding him and why? Did he take a job he didn&#8217;t tell me about?<br />
<b>Red:</b> It appears so. I&#8217;m sorry. I know that&#8217;s not the answer you want to hear.<br />
Liz: Well, call me if you find anything out.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Ressler: Got a hit on Tom&#8217;s car. Impound lot towed it in last night.<br />
Liz: Towed from where? </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Red Birch Motel ] [ BELL RINGS ] [ SOFT MUSIC PLAYS ON RADIO ]<br />
Ressler: Agents Ressler and Keen, FBI.<br />
Liz: [ Shows Tom‚Äôs photo ] We have reason to believe this man was here last night. Have you seen him?<br />
Clerk: Can&#8217;t say.<br />
Liz: His car was impounded outside Room 11.<br />
Clerk: Don&#8217;t know anything about that.<br />
Ressler: The old &#8220;can&#8217;t say, don&#8217;t know,&#8221; huh?<br />
Clerk: I mind my own business.<br />
Liz: Room 11. Can we get the key?<br />
Clerk: Sure. Soon as you get a warrant.<br />
Liz: You know what? Forget the key.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Ressler kicks in‚ö°Ô∏èthe door of Room 11. There are signs of violence ‚Äì blood on a pillow, a cracked mirror also bloody ]<br />
Ressler: We don&#8217;t know Tom was here.<br />
Liz: His car was parked outside!<br />
Ressler: All right, he came to the motel.<br />
Liz: In front of this room!<br />
Ressler: Maybe this was the only space, Liz.<br />
Liz: [ Dialing ] I&#8217;ve called Tom so many times, his mailbox is full. It&#8217;s pointless. But hearing his voice is the only thing that calms me down.<br />
Ressler: I&#8217;m gonna call CSI. If Tom was here, they&#8217;ll know.<br />
[ CELLPHONE RINGING ] [ Under a pile of covers, they find a phone indicating calls from ‚ÄúLiz.‚Äù Tom‚Äôs phone ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Tom saws at his plastic wrist binding with the pendant from Lena‚Äôs necklace ]<br />
Tom: Hey, mind if I sit?<br />
Navarro: Knock yourself out.<br />
Tom: Yeah, well, can I get a hand?<br />
Navarro: [ LAUGHS ] [ SIGHS ] Gosh, anything else I can do for you?<br />
Tom: Yeah, you could give me your gun.<br />
Navarro: [ LAUGHS ] Looks like we&#8217;ve got ourselves a comedian.<br />
[ Navarro reaches down to help Tom to his feet. Tom has cut his bindings free. He grabs the chair and smashes it over Navarro‚Äôs head, then takes his gun ]<br />
[ üí•üí•üí• Gunfight üí•üí•üí• ] [ Several goons fall ]<br />
Tom: Not that funny, is it?<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 5:9 Ruin</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief:</b> Tom Keen is dead ‚Äì of blood loss after being stabbed multiple times by Blacklister Ian Garvey, who took possession of the mysterious suitcase full of bones in the belief that they would give him power over Red. Tom took the suitcase from Garvey long enough to read the DNA results report (that Garvey had somehow acquired from the DNA database CODIS). Tom intended to share the identity of the bones with Liz when Garvey and his henchman jumped the couple in their home. Red intervened in time to save Liz‚Äôs life but Tom died in the hospital. Liz suffered a severe concussion and when she awoke, Red had to inform her not only of Tom‚Äôs death but that she has been a coma for ten months.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Leonard Cohen&#8217;s ‚ô™ &#8220;Famous Blue Raincoat&#8221; plays ]<br />
[ Liz runs through a wooded area. She is dressed for cold weather ] </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ It&#8217;s four in the morning<br />
The end of December<br />
I&#8217;m writing you now just to see if you&#8217;re any better<br />
New York is cold, but I ‚Ä¶
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Wings flutter ] [ Liz goes to a bear trap, uses a branch to spring the trap ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ ‚Ä¶ like where I&#8217;m living<br />
There&#8217;s music on Clinton Street<br />
All through the evening
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Liz goes to a cabin. She goes inside. A dog, Kate, welcomes her ]<br />
Liz: [ To dog ] Hi. Hi. I know, I know.<br />
[ Kate barks, whines ] </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ And you treated my woman<br />
To a flake of your life<br />
And when she came back<br />
She was nobody&#8217;s wife
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Liz removes her sock. Her foot is wrapped in a compression bandage. She stretches her arms then goes to a cabinet and takes some pills. She sits down to eat ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Well, I see you there<br />
With the rose in your teeth<br />
One more thin gypsy thief<br />
Well, I see Jane&#8217;s awake
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Water running; faucet turns off ] </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ She sends her regards </p>
<p>‚ô™ Ah, the last time we saw you
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Garbage disposal whirs, then overloads the generator ] </p>
<blockquote><p>
[ Music slows, distorts ]<br />
‚ô™ You looked so much older
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz goes outside to fix the stand-alone generator ]<br />
[ The generator starts, but quits after a few seconds ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz enters a store stocked with machine parts, some processed food ]<br />
Liz: Still have an L14-20 male plug? I saw one here last week.<br />
Early: On your left, by the timing belt. Genny out again?<br />
Liz: Oh, Early, if anything worked up at that place, I&#8217;d get bored.<br />
Early: [ Chuckles ] Storm&#8217;s coming. Did you see the weather?<br />
Liz: Yeah, they say ice.<br />
Early: It&#8217;s early for ice. Leaves are still on the trees, but that&#8217;s what they say. Few inches. You get that VHF radio working?<br />
Liz: It&#8217;s on my to-do list.<br />
[ Liz pays for the generator part ]<br />
Liz: [ Leaving ] Stay warm.<br />
Early: Stay warm, Grace.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz starts the generator ] [ Kate barks ]<br />
[ Liz uses an axe to split a log ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Flashback:</b><br />
Dr Nguyen: Focus now. Push yourself.<br />
[ Liz is in rehab, trying to lift arm weights ]<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 5:10 Informant (‚Ññ 118)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief: </b> Liz has returned from self-imposed exile in remote Alaska, where she single-handedly eliminated a group of criminals working for the Carlucci Crime Family who had been sent there to track down a former member who had ratted on the Family and had been placed in Alaska under witness protection. On her return from Alaska, Red finds her looking ‚Äústrong‚Äù but cautions her against her expressed lack of remorse. Her sole aim now: to seek revenge against the people who killed Tom and who put her into a 10-month-long coma and through a painful stint in rehab. She has acquired the case files for the attack against her and Tom. During her time in Alaska she left Agnes in the care of Tom‚Äôs mother, Susan (‚ÄúScottie‚Äù) Hargrave, a move which disappointed Red. In keeping with her request, Red agreed not to follow her and, for the first time, she was able to step outside of his protection, which she has found liberating.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Toronto, Ontario (Canada) ]<br />
[ Alexis Smith‚Äôs ‚ô™ ‚ÄúNightlife‚Äù plays ]<br />
[ A group of young women are at a dance spot ]<br />
Romi‚Äôs girlfriend: Don&#8217;t look now, but look, look, look, look, look!<br />
[ A pretty blond woman, Romi, makes eye contact with a cute guy across the dance floor ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ I see you there<br />
I see you there tonight<br />
Call my name
</p></blockquote>
<p>Second girlfriend: Okay, I just watched that, and I think I&#8217;m pregnant.<br />
[ LAUGHTER ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Call my name
</p></blockquote>
<p>First girlfriend: [ SINGSONG VOICE ] And he&#8217;s walking over! </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ You make me feel
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Romi‚Äôs CELLPHONE RINGS ]<br />
Romi: God. It&#8217;s Bronwyn.<br />
Girlfriend 1: What? It&#8217;s almost 11:00.<br />
Girlfriend 2: Don&#8217;t answer it.<br />
Romi: I have to. Yes? Just hang on one second.<br />
[ Romi brushes past the cute guy and goes outside ] </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ And I feel like I could do it again, all right
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Inside, air hisses. Sprays of vapor descend on the dancers ] [ CHEERING ]<br />
Romi: Can you say that again?<br />
[ An older woman, Bronwyn, is out on a busy city street trying to hail a cab ]<br />
Bronwyn: [ On phone, to Romi ] That prick Oliver threw a fit, so they bumped up the meeting. We&#8217;re presenting tomorrow, which means I need to get back tonight, and you&#8217;re‚Äì<br />
Romi: Rebooking your flight.<br />
Bronwyn: Out of Newark.<br />
Romi: My God. You&#8217;re serious?<br />
Bronwyn: What is that ‚Äì music? You&#8217;re not out on a Tuesday, are you?<br />
Romi: No, no. I, um‚Äì You hate Newark.<br />
Bronwyn: Almost as much as I hate Oliver, but the meeting&#8217;s moved, which means I need a flight. Hang on. Here&#8217;s my cab.<br />
[ HORN HONKS ]<br />
Bronwyn: Call when you get this fixed.</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Call my name
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ CELLPHONE BEEPS ]<br />
[ The young man Romi had made eye contact with earlier comes out of the dance spot ]<br />
Romi: I&#8217;m sorry. I wasn&#8217;t avoiding you earlier. It&#8217;s my boss ‚Äì she&#8217;s a bitch.</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ You make me feel
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ The young man turns around. He groans, throws up and collapses ] [ Romi gasps ]<br />
[ Romi goes back into the venue. Dozens of people appear to be dying or dead ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ again, all right, burning up light a neon light<br />
I don&#8217;t know if I&#8217;m gonna stop tonight<br />
Around and around and around, all right
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Music echoing ]<br />
[ Romi, too, gets sick and collapses ] [ Coughing ] [ Groans ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ In her almost empty home, Liz fingers the blood-stained carpet. Tearfully, she remembers moments from the night of the attack on her and Tom ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Flashback:</b><br />
[ Tom is stabbed, groans ]<br />
[ Liz screams ‚ÄúNo!‚Äù ]<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 5:11 Abraham Stern (‚Ññ 100)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief:</b> With a new sense of self-confidence, Liz is driven by the single-minded determination to find Tom‚Äôs killers. Working outside of the Task Force, she has none-the-less gained access to the case files on the attack and, also relying on her memories of the attack, has set up her apartment as a crime scene with an ad hoc evidence board. Following a tip given her by a police detective assigned to the case, she found her way to Bobby Navarro, Ian Garvey‚Äôs lead henchman, who refused to identify Garvey whom Liz has dubbed ‚ÄúDamascus‚Äù based on her memory of the type of knife Garvey used to kill Tom. Navarro did tell Liz ‚ÄúYour man wasn‚Äôt helping Nik. Nik was helping your man.‚Äù When Liz asked ‚ÄúWith what?‚Äù Navarro attacked her and Liz ended up killing him. Meanwhile, Red has freed Ressler from Henry Prescott, the dirty ‚Äúfixer‚Äù who had blackmailed Ressler over his knowledge that Ressler was involved in the altercation that led to the death of former National Security Advisor Laurel Hitchin. Ressler tried to turn over a signed confession to Cooper about the incident, but Cooper refused to read it. Instead, he put it in a drawer and handed a similar envelope to Ressler, declaring they should pass on their contents to The Powers That Be ‚Äì but only after the work of the Task Force was completed: ‚ÄúNone of us ¬≠are the people that we were before this task force started ‚Äì before Reddington.‚Äù
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Dembe drives Red in his Mercedes ] [ Red is holding the rare Lincoln penny he got from Greyson Blaise ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I haven&#8217;t felt this giddy since Herbie Hunnicutt and I pooled our box tops and sent away for the decoder ring and periscope. Why is that? What is this feeling?<br />
Dembe: You love treasures, Raymond.<br />
<b>Red:</b> And you don&#8217;t? Of course, you do. Everyone loves hidden treasures ‚Äì Yamashita‚Äôs Gold, the Oak Island Money Pit. Hell, even DB Cooper, which was more of a mystery and less of a treasure hunt, really.<br />
Dembe: That&#8217;s what you love ‚Äì the mystery.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Mystery? You know why?<br />
Dembe: Robert Louis Stevenson.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes! Edgar Allan Poe. &#8220;The Gold Bug.&#8221; Oh, what a story. It has everything ‚Äì a delirious search for treasure, the descent into madness, along with ciphers and bugs, a skull nailed to a tree. What a yarn! If he actually has the locations of the other coins, this could be a massive discovery.<br />
[ TIRES SCREECH ] [ A truck crashes into Red‚Äôs car üí•‚ÄºÔ∏èüí• leaving it upside down, throwing the penny free. Red appears stunned, with a bloody nose. Goons get out of the truck; so does Abraham Stern. He retrieves penny from the pavement ]<br />
Abraham Stern: Thank you, gentlemen. You may go. We got what I came for.<br />
[ He tosses the penny up in the air, catches it ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz is at Bobby Navarro‚Äôs apartment. She groans, removes a shard of glass from her abdomen, stanching the blood with a rag. She gets cleaning solutions from under the sink. She zips Navarro‚Äôs body into a black bag. She sweeps up broken glass, scrubs the blood from the carpet. She again uses the rag to stop her bleeding ]<br />
[ POUNDING ON DOOR ]<br />
Officer #1: Robert Navarro, MPD. We need you to open the door, please.<br />
Officer #2: Let&#8217;s go, Bobby, open up.<br />
Officer #1: We&#8217;re here with the super. We&#8217;re coming in, you hear?<br />
[ Liz stuffs the bloody rag into the sink, then ducks into a closet ] [ Police enter ]<br />
Super: Guy&#8217;s constantly got people coming and going. Music all night.<br />
Officer #2: Sir, if could you step outside.<br />
Super: I ain&#8217;t waiting outside. I know the rules. What&#8217;d he do? Drugs? It&#8217;s drugs, right?<br />
Officer #2: Apartment&#8217;s clear.<br />
Super: You find something wrong, you gotta tell me. That&#8217;s how it works.</p>

‚ãò‚ãô<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red briefs the Task Force ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> In recent years, Federal Reserve Notes issued in the 1930s have turned up in Manila and Singapore.<br />
Ressler: [ Reads from bill projected above ] &#8220;The United States of America will pay to the bearer on demand $100,000.&#8221; How many of these notes are floating around?<br />
<b>Red:</b> None, according to your government. It denies issuing any such notes and insists the few that have turned up are counterfeit.<br />
Samar: I thought this was about your penny.<br />
<b>Red:</b> It is because without the pennies, we will never find the notes or the man who&#8217;s killing to get them.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

Frank Dobbs: Please. I&#8217;ll do anything.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Aram: &#8220;Pennies&#8221; ‚Äì wasn&#8217;t there only one?<br />
<b>Red:</b> No, there are four. Bronze, minted in 1943.<br />
Cooper: Before stealing it, you were willing to spend $3 million of our money to buy one of the pennies at auction.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Collectors value them because they believe they were minted in error ‚Äì bronze one-offs when every other penny was made of copper. But what collectors don&#8217;t know, what makes them truly valuable, is not that they were a mistake, but that there is a code put there by the man who minted them ‚Äì a map to a vast fortune.<br />
Aram: The lost Federal Reserve Notes that Treasury claims it never made.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Finding the long-lost notes is a quest for the financial holy grail. Hundreds of millions of dollars, redeemable upon request.<br />
Ressler: And the man who attacked you knew this?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Aram, if you would.<br />
Aram: Three security guards murdered at the Sharjah Museum in Dubai, an Italian art collector dies when his home is consumed by a fire set by an unknown arsonist, and just last night, an antiques dealer murdered in Georgetown.<br />
<b>Red:</b> After informing our Blacklister that I&#8217;d arranged to meet with him. That&#8217;s how he got the where and the when, and he used that intel to ambush me.<br />
Cooper: Three incidents, presumably only three pennies That leaves him one short.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Abraham Stern: You were once an insurance investigator. Funny I have a personal situation involving a rare coin. Perhaps we could help each other.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Samar: Any indication he knows where this last penny is?<br />
<b>Red:</b> No, and if he gets it, he gets the code and the treasure, which means we need to locate that penny before he does.<br />
Cooper: Our only interest is in stopping this guy. The treasure&#8217;s not our concern.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Oh, don&#8217;t be such a spoilsport. This could be such fun! Where&#8217;s your sense of adventure?<br />
Aram: I think it sounds like fun.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Thank you, Aram. That&#8217;s the spirit. Harold, you could learn a thing or two from your subordinates.</p>

<p>&nbsp;<br />
Aram: Okay. Check this out. I think I may have located the fourth penny. All right, after the coins were minted, they disappeared for about 30 years. No record of them anywhere. But then, in 1975, they started to appear at auctions. The missing penny was last sold in 1984, and, according to the bill of sale, the man who bought it passed away two years ago.<br />

Aram: Yes, and it was included in an extensive art collection that he left to the University of Pennsylvania.<br />

Aram: Yes and no. I spoke to the head of donations at the university, and she says the coin is on loan at the Gabor Museum.<br />
Cooper: Ressler and Navabi, get to the museum. Find out what they know.</p>

<b>Red:</b> The same year he put the cipher on the coins.<br />

<b>Red:</b> ‚Äì Whoops.<br />
