<b>Red:</b> I didn&#8217;t take anything else.<br />
Cooper: Evidence was logged in material to the disappearance of Robert Navarro a person of interest in the death of Tom Keen. You didn&#8217;t take it?<br />
<b>Red:</b> No, I did not.</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Oh, oh Ooh, a legend Hey
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Cooper holds out the penny. Red snatches it and leaves ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Glen is resting comfortably in the hospital as Liz feeds him scoops of pudding or jello, a juice box with a bendy straw nearby. His room if full of balloons and flowers ] [ A horseshoe shaped flower arrangement is placed in near his bed ]<br />
Glen: Hey Ooh-la-la!<br />
Hospital Aide: This one says, [ Reading ]  &#8220;Dear Glen, Glad you&#8217;re okay and recovering well. Thank you for all you do. R.R.&#8221;<br />
Glen: Secret admirer. One of many.<br />
Aide: [ Reading ]  &#8220;P.S. To whom it may concern, Glen is a licentious cur.&#8221;<br />
Glen: What? I don&#8217;t know what licentious means [ SIGHS ] but I&#8217;m pretty sure he meant it as a compliment.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz arrives at Red‚Äôs suite ]<br />
Liz: Is everything okay? Dembe said it was urgent.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You&#8217;re to be congratulated. I may be old, but I&#8217;m not an old fool, and you completely hoodwinked me and Harold. He thinks I stole a bloody rag from evidence.<br />
Liz: Right. About that‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> You were the anonymous tip. You told the MPD that the penny was about to be stolen. You knew if they stopped the robbery in progress, they&#8217;d book the penny into evidence. And you didn&#8217;t call me to help me steal the penny or to distract you from your obsession with Tom&#8217;s killer. You called me to help me help you retrieve a rag covered in your blood evidence that might have convicted you of murdering Robert Navarro.<br />
Liz: I did not intend to kill him. I intended to get him to identify Tom&#8217;s killer. He got the upper hand. There was a fight.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Where&#8217;s the body? Cooper says it&#8217;s a missing-persons case, but if they find that corpse‚Äì<br />
Liz: That&#8217;s not gonna happen.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;d like to make sure of that.<br />
Liz: I already have. And in the process, I discovered Navarro had a glass eye.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Look at that.<br />
Liz: Wait till you see this. Some kind of next-gen technology. I&#8217;m sorry I tricked you. I had no idea what else to do, but now I do, and I need your help to do it. Will you help me?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Of course I&#8217;ll help you.<br />
[ Red squints and reaches behind Liz‚Äôs ear ]<br />
Liz: What?<br />
[ Red produces the penny ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Ohh.<br />
Liz: Your penny! Wait. Does this mean you found your treasure or no?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;ve had my eye on a castle in Trieste. I&#8217;m flying over there in an hour to make a ridiculously large offer on it. Care to join me?<br />
[ DOOR OPENS, CLOSES ] [ A man enters with a box ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Oh, Bernard!<br />
Bernard: You look ‚Äì incomplete.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ CHUCKLES ] [ LAUGHS ] I just can&#8217;t believe that&#8217;s it.<br />
Bernard: Found in a trunk gathering dust in Surrey.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Hidden treasure, indeed.<br />
Bernard: Authentication papers are inside.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Ah. [ Hands Bernard the penny ] As promised.<br />
Liz: Wait, wait, wait, wait, wait. You&#8217;re gonna use your penny to buy that?<br />
<b>Red:</b> A bargain at twice the price.<br />
Liz: [ WHISPERS ] That penny&#8217;s worth $3 million.<br />
Bernard: And this is Winston Churchill&#8217;s hat.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Solemnly ] The Homburg he wore during The Blitz. Under its brim, he beat back Hitler with style and grace and unwavering confidence. I&#8217;m an eager, if unworthy, heir.<br />
[ Red puts on the hat ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> What do you think? Be brutal.<br />
Liz: It&#8217;s kind of amazing.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Laughs ] I&#8217;ll take amazing.</p>

<h3>‚≠ï Script 5:12 The Cook (‚Ññ 56)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief: </b>Liz hoodwinked both Red and the Cooper by using material evidence (a valuable penny) associated with Blacklister Abraham Stern to steal material evidence (a bloody rag) from police evidence files linking her to the death of Bobby Navarro, a man she believes worked for the man who killed Tom, Blacklister Ian Garvey, who she knows only as the ‚Äòman with the Damascus knife.‚Äô Before she killed Navarro in an altercation, Navarro told her that her ex-fianc√©, ER MD Nik Korpal, was helping Tom, not the other way around. She still does not know (though Red does) that Nik was helping Tom ID bones left for Liz by Mr Kaplan, Red‚Äôs deceased long-time cleaner, to reveal a buried secret of Red‚Äôs. Tom learned whose bones they were from DNA analysis but died before he could tell Liz. Ian Garvey now has the bones, unbeknowst to either Red or Liz. To dispose of Navarro‚Äôs body, Liz used the methods employed by S1 Blacklister Stanley Kornish (The Stewmaker) ~ using chemicals to dissolve his body and flush it down a motel room‚Äôs bathtub drain. In this process, Liz discovered that Navarro had a glass eye equipped with ‚Äúnext gen‚Äù electronics, whose existence she has shared with Red.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Wall of Voodoo&#8217;s ‚ô™ &#8220;Ring of Fire&#8221; plays ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Love is a burning thing<br />
And it makes a fiery ring<br />
I was bound by wild desire<br />
I fell into a ring of fire </p>
<p>‚ô™ I fell into a burning ring of fire<br />
I went down, down, down, and the flames got higher<br />
And it burns, burns, burns<br />
The ring of fire<br />
The ring of fire<br />
The ring of fire </p>
<p>‚ô™ The taste of love is sweet<br />
When hearts like ours meet<br />
I fell for you like a child<br />
Oh, but the fire went wild<br />
I fell into a burning ring of fire
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ A man with a bald head and scarred back turns on burners in a kitchen. He soaks his clothes in liquid and puts them on wet. He hangs jars with a cloudy liquid from rope strung across a living room. The man sits down in a comfortable chair, cracks open a beer and lights one end of the rope with a lighter. The flame moves along the rope, igniting the liquid in the jars which fall and set the room ablaze. The man smiles ]<br />
[ A woman is heard outside the door ]<br />
Woman: Is someone there? I‚Äôm going to call the cops.<br />
[ The woman opens the door and is engulfed in flames ] [ SCREAMS ]<br />
[ The man lifts his bottle to the woman ]<br />
[ The man gathers up his ladder and bag and leaves ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ I went down, down, down, and the flames got higher<br />
And it burns, burns, burns<br />
The ring of fire<br />
The ring of fire<br />
The ring of fire </p>
<p>‚ô™ Yes, it burns, burns, burns<br />
The ring of fire<br />
The ring of fire<br />
The ring of fire
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Liz: I got your message. You found someone who can analyze Navarro&#8217;s glass eye?<br />
<b>Red:</b> He can see us this afternoon. Did you bring it?<br />
Liz: I know I&#8217;m gonna have to answer for what I&#8217;ve done, but right now all that matters is we find out who put that in Navarro&#8217;s head and whether it can lead us to Tom&#8217;s killers ‚Äì and the truth.<br />
<b>Red:</b> The truth?<br />
Liz: The last time I spoke to Tom, he told me, &#8220;I figured it out ‚Äì Why Nik died, everything.&#8221; That&#8217;s why I went home ‚Äì to find the truth. But they got to him first.<br />
<b>Red:</b> My contact lives with his mother. She&#8217;s not particularly fond of me. I&#8217;m not quite sure if it&#8217;s actually me or what I represent. I believe she feels I&#8217;m a bad influence on her son. I thought a gesture of goodwill might smooth things over.<br />
Liz: You think an empty terrarium is goodwill? Whoa!<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ LAUGHS ] The mother&#8217;s family operates a pet caf√© in Kyoto. You can enjoy the most savory tsukemen ramen in and around a variety of animals native to Japan ‚Äì cormorants, katydids, the occasional tanuki.<br />
Liz: And you thought spiders would be a welcome addition?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Joro spiders. In Japanese folklore, the joro is said to be able to change its appearance to that of a beautiful woman who seduces men, binding them in her web before devouring them. Hence its name &#8220;joro-gumo,&#8221; or &#8220;whore spider.&#8221;<br />
Liz: Oh.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Here&#8217;s the mother&#8217;s work address and a note. If you could please drop them off?<br />
Liz: No! Me?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I have a time-sensitive case for the Task Force. You did ask me to hold up my part of that deal in your absence.<br />
Liz: Do you know what Tom was talking about? When he said he figured it out?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Tom was a man of many truths. Which of those he was going to divulge, I can&#8217;t say.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<b>Red:</b> My sincere apologies. I hope Paris has taken good care of you. [ To Paris: ] Tea, please.<br />
Samar: He made me an egg dish I can&#8217;t even pronounce. It was divine. As is your suite, which is why in the future, I think we should meet elsewhere.<br />
<b>Red:</b> And why is that?<br />
Samar: Because being here gives me the impression that crime pays.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ LAUGHS ] What are the most expensive crimes in America?<br />
Samar: Expensive?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Top three.<br />
Samar: Theft, armed robbery‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> Arson. 500,000 arson fires occur each year, costing over $2 billion in property loss.<br />
Samar: [ Reading ] &#8220;Husband and wife die in house fire.&#8221;<br />
<b>Red:</b> In those 500,000 fires, about 500 people die ‚Äì one per thousand. Arsonists are many things, but rarely premeditating murderers.<br />
Samar: [ Reading ] &#8220;An accelerant was found, but no motive or suspect.&#8221;<br />
<b>Red:</b> Because they&#8217;re looking at the case the wrong way. This wasn&#8217;t arson that resulted in murder. This was a murder committed by arson.<br />
Samar: But you said arsonists are rarely murderers.<br />
<b>Red:</b> A fact which makes The Cook both rare and dangerous and the next name on the Blacklist.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Aram: Does he know how many fires?<br />
Ressler: Or how many victims?<br />
Samar: No and no.<br />
Ressler: But he says this &#8220;Cook&#8221; is a serial killer posing as an arsonist.<br />
Cooper: And yet he can&#8217;t I.D. The Cook, and the only fire he told us about is one that arson investigators don&#8217;t believe was a homicide.<br />
Ressler: I suppose Reddington knows better.<br />
Samar: No, but he knows someone who does. Earl Fagen.<br />
Aram: The arson investigator slash arsonist?<br />
Cooper: Fagen hid in plain sight for years, was lead investigator on a dozen fires that he set. No one knows more about fire or the men and women who set them.<br />
Samar: Reddington says he can help us find The Cook.<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 5:13 The Invisible Hand (‚Ññ 63)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief:</b> Red, with Dembe‚Äôs encouragement, has finally confessed to Liz that he was somehow implicated in Tom‚Äôs death: ‚ÄúI have a secret, and I need to keep it even from you.‚Äù Liz knows the secret involves an ‚Äúitem‚Äù but not what the item may be (i.e. a suitcase with a skeleton inside, the identity of which Tom had discovered). Red says Tom died because he disregarded Red‚Äôs warning not to pursue it. Liz has vowed to unearth ‚Äúthe truth‚Äù because Tom wanted her to know what he found out. She will work with Red but they are at cross-purposes. Meanwhile, Red helped the task force in order to obtain parole for a convicted arsonist whose help he plans to use in the future.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A restaurant in New York City ]<br />
Zeke: Yeah, so you&#8217;ve got everything? Wonderful. Thank you so much for coming, and drive carefully. All right, we look forward to having you again.<br />
Diner Patron: Bye, Zeke.<br />
[ Diner patron leaves. Zeke enters a side room with a small group ]<br />
[ LAUGHTER ]<br />
Emma: Zeke! Perfect timing. Tim was just telling us how Sophia picked him up at a bar.<br />
Stephen Altman: She used to be ¬≠the shyest girl in school.<br />
Tim Gorman: Well, she wasn&#8217;t shy with me.<br />
Sophia: Can we please change the subject?<br />
Bobby: Sure. I want to hear more about what Tim does for a living.<br />
Tim: I told you. I make security products.<br />
Stephen: Handguns. You make the cheapest handguns on the market today.<br />
Emma: You flood poor cities with guns that have no value to anyone but criminals. Your sales drive up homicide rates.<br />
Bobby: You profit off misery.<br />
Stephen: That&#8217;s blood money, Tim.<br />
Tim: What the hell is this? It isn&#8217;t against the law to sell guns.<br />
Stephen: No, it isn&#8217;t. In fact, the law protects gun makers like you from being sued.<br />
Tim: Is that why you brought me here, to insult me?<br />
Stephen: We all brought you here. Not to insult you. To punish you.<br />
[ Stephen hits Tim on the side of head with a beer bottle. When Tim wakes up he is in a grave with duct tape over his mouth. Five figures in hazmat suits and masks surround the grave. One by one, they take a shovel and begin to shovel dirt into it ]<br />
[ MUFFLED GROAN, SHOUTING ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ KNOCKS ON DOOR ]<br />
Detective Singleton: Keen, I have your husband&#8217;s personal effects.<br />
[ Liz opens her door ]<br />
Singleton: How&#8217;d you do it?<br />
Liz: Excuse me?<br />
Singleton: I know you killed Navarro, and I know you left that bloody rag behind at his apartment. What I don&#8217;t know is how you broke into evidence lockup and stole it before it was sent to the lab.<br />
Liz: Someone broke into the evidence lockup?<br />
Singleton: I&#8217;m here to deliver Tom&#8217;s things in person‚Äì<br />
Liz: Step back.<br />
Singleton: And all you do is lie.<br />
Liz: You know, you better be careful, Detective, because no matter what you believe, you&#8217;re still talking to a Federal agent.<br />
Singleton: We&#8217;ll see how cool you are when I do come to arrest you. Because that day is coming.<br />
Liz: Thank you for bringing Tom&#8217;s things.<br />
[ Liz goes through the stuff Singleton brought. She finds a key. She goes into a storage locker and pulls out a locked case. She uses the key to open it ] [ LOCK CLICKS ] [ Inside the case she finds a gun, a notebook and some other items. She opens the notebook to a page with the name OLEANDER written across the top. Tom had divided the page into sections: Person, Place, Thing ‚Äì each with various items listed; a work in progress ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ DEVICE BEEPING ] [ TELEPHONE RINGS ]<br />
Cooper: [ On phone ] Cooper here.<br />
Liz: I need your help.<br />
&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>On tv: </b><br />
<b>Reporter:</b> Here outside the upstate New York town of Harrington, locals have long told ghost stories about these abandoned fields and the walking dead who haunt them. Last night for a few teens, those stories became all too real.
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Red and Samar watch the tv broadcast at the pet care place Red uses for money laundering. Red is holding a little white dog ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Reporter:</b> Alex, can you tell us what happened?<br />
<b>Alex:</b> You know, we hopped the fence and walked into the fields, you know, on a dare, and that&#8217;s when I saw the new grave.
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Red cuddles the puppy, gives it a little kiss ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Reporter:</b> So far, authorities have uncovered one dead body and are continuing to investigate.
</p></blockquote>
<p><b>Red:</b> I have to say, ¬≠I would&#8217;ve done exactly the same when I was a kid. It&#8217;s a ghost story ‚Äì creepy woods, rumors of corpses walking around in the dead of night.<br />
Samar: Is that your dog, or a customer&#8217;s?<br />
<b>Red:</b> What a dear. Yes. You&#8217;re a good girl.<br />
[ Red kisses the dog again and puts it down ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> All right, off you go. [ LAUGHS ] A few days ago, Tim Gorman, the owner of Ballistic-Nine, a controversial ¬≠gun manufacturing company based in Reading, Pennsylvania, disappeared.<br />
Samar: That&#8217;s who&#8217;s in the shallow grave, Tim Gorman, the businessman who makes gun a fifth the price of an iPhone?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Murdered, I believe, by a provocative group known as The Invisible Hand.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Members of The Invisible Hand are on a conference call ]<br />
Stephen: I saw the news. They found Gorman.<br />
Zeke: Yeah, not just Gorman. Hang on, I want to conference in Sophia.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Samar: So, they&#8217;re vigilantes going after criminals the legal system has failed to convict?<br />
<b>Red:</b> The criminals here aren&#8217;t really criminals at all. That&#8217;s the point. The Invisible Hand chooses targets who aren&#8217;t actually aren&#8217;t committing crimes under existing law.<br />
Samar: Like Tim Gorman. Everything he did was perfectly legal.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes, but morally reprehensible in the eyes of The Hand. ‚ÄúEyes of The Hand.‚Äù What an odd turn of phrase.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Sophia is driving. Her daughter is in the back in a car seat ]<br />
Sophia: I&#8217;m on.<br />
Everly: Mommy, Mommy ‚Äì<br />
Sophia: Everly, baby, Mommy has to take this call. Shh.<br />
Stephen: We don&#8217;t really have time for this.<br />
Sophia: I&#8217;m sorry, but I wasn&#8217;t exactly expecting the call.<br />
Zeke: Look, can we all just stay focused, please? Now, we all saw the news. As we speak, the police are digging up the entire site. We&#8217;ll be exposed‚Äì<br />
Stephen: You don&#8217;t know that.<br />
Sophia: Oh, my God.<br />
Everly: Mom!<br />
Emma: I agree with Stephen. We&#8217;ve always covered our tracks. Nothing at the site leads back to us.<br />
Bobby: Look, let me do some sniffing around at the paper. I can call a few sources, see what the police really know.<br />
Stephen: Great. We meet up later at Zeke&#8217;s.</p>

Bobby: ¬≠How did they know?<br />

Stephen: That&#8217;s exactly why ¬≠I didn&#8217;t tell you, &#8217;cause I knew none of you would step up to the plate and finish what we started. We finally got Anna Hopkins. Nothing else matters.<br />
Bobby: Nothing matters to you, &#8217;cause you&#8217;re dying. We have things to live for.<br />
Stephen: For now, until you get sick. Don&#8217;t think that you won&#8217;t.<br />
Bobby: We have kids and families. We love you, S-Stephen, but you s-should&#8217;ve told us. Let us decide for ourselves.<br />

Bobby: ¬≠Yeah. [ PANTING ] Go. I won&#8217;t make it to a hospital. You finish what we started.<br />
[ GROANS ] [ VAN DOOR OPENS ] [ DOOR CLOSES ] </p>

Ressler: And you deny nothing?<br />

Ressler: And, uh, what story is this?<br />
Stephen: The story of six kids who lived on the same cul-de-sac in an idyllic town, six kids who thought the world was a beautiful place where wonderful things would happen if they just worked hard, played by the rules if they were just good people. Then one day, they watched while everyone they loved got sick and died. Killers never held responsible. But you know what those idealistic kids did? They stayed idealistic. They went out into the world to try and change things, make it a better place, pursued careers to help the powerless, to unearth the truth and expose the bad guys, and they tried to see the good in the world. And you know what they learned? It doesn&#8217;t work. The world hadn&#8217;t changed. They hadn&#8217;t made it a better place. And then one of our six heroes died of the same bone cancer that took his mom and his dad. The other five met up after years away at his funeral, and there, standing over his coffin, a plan emerged, a new plan to change the world, only this time being as ruthless with the world as it had been with them.<br />
Ressler: And this vigilante justice You really think that that&#8217;s what this world needs?<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 5:14 Mr Raleigh Sinclair III (‚Ññ 51)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief:</b> Liz and Red are on a race against time ‚Äì and each other ‚Äì to locate the suitcase containing a skeleton. Liz knows it only as an ‚Äúitem‚Äù which will reveal to her ‚Äúthe truth‚Äù ‚Äì a secret of Red‚Äôs ‚Äì that Tom wanted her to know. Red knows that Mr Kaplan left the suitcase for Liz but Tom purloined it. Determined to identify it himself before telling Liz, Tom got killed for his trouble. It is now in the hands of Tom‚Äôs murderer, Ian Garvey, who knows its value to Red. In the search for Tom‚Äôs killer, Liz found among Tom‚Äôs things a reference to an ‚ÄúOleander‚Äù who Cooper has told her was a Russian operative during the Cold War. Following the tip from Cooper leads Liz to Dominic Wilkerson. This turns out to be ‚ÄúDom,‚Äù Liz‚Äôs own grandfather (and Red‚Äôs gruff, reclusive, occasional antagonist). Dom claims only a passing familiarity with former Soviet agents, but recognizes Liz when she tells him Katarina Rostova (his own daughter) was her mother. He does not tell Liz he is her grandfather ‚Äì or that he himself is Oleander. He says he does not know if Katarina is still alive. Meanwhile, Red is tracking the suitcase through the Nash Syndicate, a drug operation which Red has learned is protected or run by cops. The final scene of Episode 5:13 shows that, not only does Ian Garvey himself wear a badge, but Detective Singleton, the cop working Tom‚Äôs case, is in cahoots with him.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Brian Barrett sits down on a city bench next to Mr Raleigh Sinclair III ]<br />
Mr Raleigh Sinclair III: You&#8217;re late.<br />
Brian Barrett: I came as soon as I could. The train was delayed.<br />
Sinclair: I was very clear about being punctual.<br />
Brian: What? You&#8217;re joking, right? I&#8217;m five minutes late.<br />
Sinclair: Mr. Barrett, if this were to work, it will depend entirely on- on the routines and the patterns that I set forth. And as you&#8217;re failing already, I doubt your ability to stay the course over time.<br />
Brian: I-It won&#8217;t happen again.<br />
Sinclair: Tell me again about that day how you found her, how it felt.<br />
Brian: What?<br />
Sinclair: Walk me through what happened with Nicki. You came home early because?<br />
Brian: We&#8217;d been having problems. I wanted to surprise her. I remember her shoes. There was a set of keys on the table.<br />
Sinclair: Don&#8217;t tell me what you saw. Tell me what you felt, what you feel.<br />
Brian: I felt‚Äì </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Flashback:</b> A man and woman are having sex.<br />
Nicole: [ MOANS ]
</p></blockquote>
<p>Brian: ‚Äìrage. Nothing else.</p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Flashback:</b><br />
Nicole: [ MOANING CONTINUES ]
</p></blockquote>
<p>Brian: I wasn&#8217;t hurt or sad or betrayed. All I felt was rage ‚Äì like the only thing that mattered was that she‚Äì </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Flashback:</b><br />
Nicole: [ MOANING CONTINUES ]
</p></blockquote>
<p>Brian: ‚ÄìI wanted ‚Äì I wanted to hurt her. Not him. Her.</p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Flashback:</b><br />
Nicole: [ MOANING CONTINUES ]
</p></blockquote>
<p>Sinclair: That feeling you have right now ‚Äì that anger ‚Äì I want you to hold on to that, because that malice you feel in your heart is more dependable than any contract killer or hit man or third person. Can you do that, Brian? Is your hatred big enough to sustain you? </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Flashback:</b><br />
Nicole: [ MOANING CONTINUES ]
</p></blockquote>
<p>Brian: Yes.<br />
Sinclair: You remember that. I will contact you again when you have gathered the items on this list.<br />
Brian: [ Reading ] Three pairs of yellow running shoes, an iPhone, an apartment on Washington Place?<br />
Sinclair: It&#8217;s a lovely little unit. Just around the corner.<br />
Brian: You want me to rent an apartment in Manhattan?<br />
Sinclair: You want a perfect alibi for murdering your wife?<br />
Brian: I&#8217;ll do it today.<br />
Sinclair: When you&#8217;re watching your wife die, it it will be well worth the wait.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red‚Äôs suite. Liz enters ]<br />
Liz: That detective, Singleton, he was in my apartment while I was out.‚Äì<br />
[ Liz hands Red photos from a surveillance camera ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> What?<br />
Liz: ‚ÄìNo warrant. Just broke in.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Where did you get these?<br />
Liz: I installed cameras in my house. I had my suspicions, and now I have proof. The lead detective investigating Tom&#8217;s murder is a dirty cop.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Where are you on reinstatement?<br />
Liz: I have my fitness-for-duty evaluation tomorrow.<br />
<b>Red:</b> 50 minutes of pure reflection and self-evaluation.<br />
Liz: You&#8217;ve been to therapy?<br />
<b>Red:</b> God, yes. Therapy helped me become ‚Äì an entirely different person.<br />
[ CELLPHONE CHIMES ]<br />
Dembe: Agent Navabi is ready to meet.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Several years ago, one of my bankers in Liechtenstein shared with me some unpublished works by Carl Jung ‚Äì handwritten notes on napkins, journals, and such. It was easily the most enlightening, consequential five days I&#8217;ve ever spent in a chalet.<br />
Dembe: What about that week in Davos?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes. Well. That was a cottage.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A wine cellar-style restaurant ‚ÄúAntique Garage‚Äù ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Agent Navabi, are you familiar with the Innocence Project?<br />
Samar: Of course. They use DNA evidence to exonerate the wrongfully convicted.<br />

[ Red slides a newspaper across the table to Samar. The headline reads: ‚ÄúDeMARCO CLEARED BY EYEWITNESS TESTIMONY‚Äù ]<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 5:15 Pattie Sue Edwards (‚Ññ 68)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief: </b> Red has continued collecting talented criminals as he appeases the Task Force by delivering other killers. These include arsonist Earl Fagan and Mr Raleigh Sinclair III (‚ÄúThe Alibi‚Äù) who creates doppelgangers. He and Liz have learned from ‚ÄúThe Toymaker‚Äù Cleveland Bandicott that the man who had him devise Bobby Navarro‚Äôs GPS-tracking electronic eye was likely a cop. Meanwhile, unknown to Liz and Red, that man was Ian Garvey, a US Marshall and is apparently a ‚Äúdirty cop.‚Äù Ian Garvey killed Tom and is in possession the suitcase containing a skeleton that Mr Kaplan intended for Liz but which Red is desperate to claim before Liz finds out where or what it is. Singleton, the detective investigating Tom‚Äôs murder, has twice broken in to Liz‚Äôs apartment. The second time, she confronted Singleton and threatened to turn him in for burglary, but he showed her photos linking Red to her and threatened to turn her! in for working for Red. To prove she had a legitimate reason for associating with Red, she got Cooper‚Äôs permission to bring Singleton to the black site in the Post Office and inform him about the work of the Reddington Task Force.
</p></blockquote>

<h2>üî¥ Script: 5:16 The Capricorn Killer (‚Ññ 19)</h2>

Program air date: 3/14/2018 in the US<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 5:16 The Capricorn Killer (‚Ññ 19)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief: </b>Norman Singleton, the detective investigating Tom Keen‚Äôs murder, has been murdered by Tom Keen‚Äôs killer, Ian Garvey, his co-worker, a US marshall and ‚Äúdirty cop‚Äù who runs a group of thugs aligned with the Nash drug syndicate. Singleton and Liz attempted to draw out Tom‚Äôs killer, but Garvey caught Singleton in the process. Liz has recognized Garvey among the cops at the scene of Singleton‚Äôs stabbing as ‚ÄúDamascus‚Äù ‚Äì the man with the Damascus knife ‚Äì from the night of Tom‚Äôs murder. Garvey wanted a suitcase/duffel containing a skeleton left for Liz by Mr Kaplan but intercepted by Tom. Garvey tracked the bones to Tom after DNA from the bones was ID‚Äôd by a government computer database. Garvey took the skeleton planning to use its identity to blackmail Red. He killed Tom after Tom refused to connect him with Red. Both Liz and Red want to retrieve the skeleton, but Liz knows of it only as an ‚Äúitem‚Äù that will tell her ‚Äúthe truth‚Äù that Red has told her has to do with him ‚Äì but which must ‚Äúremain a secret, even from you.‚Äù
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ An FBI helicopter lands in a wooded area near Huntington PA ]<br />
Sergeant Chris Phalen: Agent Graves? Sergeant Phalen. State Police. We spoke on the phone.<br />
Agent Brandon Graves: Yes, sir.<br />
Sergeant Phalen: This way.<br />
Agent Graves: So, when did this happen?<br />
Phalen: Just after 6:00 last night. A young couple staying at the lodge went out for a hike straight off one of the trails. Bradford PD got the call after 7:00, notified us.<br />
Graves: Anyone spoken to the press?<br />
Phalen: Responding officer and a couple of the guys from Troop P are the only ones who&#8217;ve seen the site. Some of the men are pretty shook up. Think it could be him?<br />
Graves: I sincerely doubt that.<br />
Phalen: Right, but if it is him and you need my department to issue a BOLO or set a perimeter ‚Äì<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ POLICE RADIO CHATTER ] [ INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS ]<br />
[ A body is propped upright by the skull of a goat. The corpse‚Äôs arms are tied behind its back. Branches with berries are stuck in the eye sockets of the goat‚Äôs skull ]<br />
Phalen: That&#8217;s him, right? I mean, who else?<br />
[ Seen from the front, a sword‚Äôs hilt sticks out of the dead man‚Äôs mouth ]<br />
Graves: Issue that BOLO. Have your men set a perimeter and circulate that sketch we have on file.<br />
[ Phalen leaves ] [ Graves makes a call ] [ CELLPHONE DIALING ] [ RINGS ]<br />
Graves: Hey. Do me a favor. There&#8217;s an agent I need you to find right away. She&#8217;s outta DC ‚Äì Name&#8217;s Elizabeth Keen.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ CHURCH BELLS TOLLING ]<br />
[ Liz watches from a car as the casket containing the body of murdered Detective Norman Singleton is loaded into a hearse. US Marshall Ian Garvey, the man Liz knows murdered both Singleton and Tom, is one of the pallbearers. She watches as Garvey offers condolences to Singleton‚Äôs ex-wife and his two daughters ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Cooper‚Äôs Office ]<br />
Liz: He went to his funeral. He was a pallbearer. A pallbearer!<br />
Cooper: And while he was doing that, a witness came forward who saw Garvey kill Singleton.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ A young man, Tony Mejia, points to a photo of Detective Singleton in a book ]<br />
Interrogator: Now, the killer can you describe him to me?<br />
Tony: He had glasses. Black glasses.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Liz: Well, I saw Garvey kill Tom. A lot of good that did me.<br />
Cooper: I&#8217;ve already referred Garvey&#8217;s case to the Marshal&#8217;s Office of Internal Affairs. And now this. It&#8217;s a big break. It&#8217;s okay to get your hopes up.<br />
Liz: You&#8217;ve spoken to this witness? Is he credible? &#8216;Cause if he is, then my testimony‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> Will also be credible. Any questions about your memory will go away. So will Mr.<br />
Garvey.<br />
Liz: And you want that?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Not until I get what I want.<br />
Liz: I told him about the duffel bag.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Garvey provides protection for the Nash Syndicate. I know some of the players. I&#8217;ll shake them loose while the Task Force questions the witness.<br />
Liz: Where is the witness? Can I question him?<br />
Cooper: He&#8217;s not here. And, no, you can&#8217;t.<br />
Liz: This is Tom&#8217;s killer we&#8217;re talking about.<br />
Cooper: Which is why you can&#8217;t be involved. A defense lawyer would need all of a minute to convince a jury to disregard any part of a case you build against Garvey. You&#8217;re the widow and star witness. You can&#8217;t also be the investigating officer.<br />
Liz: So, while you and Reddington go after Garvey, I&#8217;m supposed to, what, read a book?<br />
Cooper: Actually, I have a case.<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m only interested in the man who murdered Tom and finding out the secret that got him killed.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m going to help with the former and prevent the latter. 50-50 split. Like a good divorce. Harold.<br />
[ Red leaves ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Cooper: About the case.<br />
Liz: Pass.<br />
Cooper: Agent Keen. This came directly from Quantico. They specifically requested you. Said it&#8217;s a cold case you&#8217;d be familiar with. Someone called the Capricorn Killer. Sound familiar?<br />
Liz: Yeah, it does.<br />
Cooper: Good. Because I told them they have the full support of you and this Task Force. Reddington and I will stay on Garvey, but I need you to tell us about Capricorn.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz briefs the task force ]<br />
Liz: His first victim was a female college professor found in Tacoma in 2010. Cause of death was ligature strangulation, but the staging was disturbing, so much that we believe there must be some religious or cult affiliation. Then, six months later, it happened again in Memphis. Then Charlotte. Idaho Falls. Seven victims in four years. Each one found in remote, inhospitable environments, and each one strangled and posed and placed using a hand-forged sword and holding the skull of a horned goat.<br />
Aram: Hence the name Capricorn. Sign of the goat.<br />
Liz: This astrological symbol also represents a creature whose natural ability allows them to survive in inhospitable environments. It also characterizes panic and fear.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ The crime site ]<br />
Agent Graves: Agent Keen? Brandon Graves. Pittsburgh Field Office.<br />
Liz: Agents Ressler and Navabi.<br />
Graves: This way.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Cooper: Your profile it was different from the others?<br />
Liz: Slightly. We all agreed the unsub was likely a white male, 40s, small in stature, and well organized.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Liz: He was transitory. A long-haul trucker, perhaps, or some other kind of blue-collar job that required travel, and that movement gave him confidence.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Liz: So much so that his killings accelerated at an alarming rate.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Liz: I thought he would stop.<br />
Graves: Which he did. Went silent. The Bureau thought he was dead or had been arrested.<br />
Ressler: Until today.<br />
Samar: How is your theory different?<br />
Liz: Well, his killings accelerated so quickly, I thought he would feel out of control. Hold back. Go dormant for a while. Others thought he had stopped. I thought he would return.<br />

<h2>üî¥ Script: 5:17 Anna-Garcia Duerte (‚Ññ 25)</h2>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Program air date: 4/4/2018 in the US<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 5:17 Anna-Gracia Duerte (‚Ññ 25)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief: </b> US Marshal Ian Garvey has murdered Detective Norman Singleton, who was investigating the murder of Liz‚Äôs husband Tom Keen. Garvey himself murdered Tom and is in the possession of a skeleton Mr Kaplan left for Liz. Red does not want the identity of the skeleton disclosed and to keep this secret he abducted the eye witness to Singleton‚Äôs murder whose testimony against Garvey could have bolstered Liz‚Äôs, whose own testimony may be questioned due to a concussion she suffered during the attack on her and Tom that left her comatose for 10 months. Garvey and Red are at a stand-off over the bones, but Red has warned Garvey to leave Liz alone and has promised him he will kill him once he gets the skeleton back. Garvey claims to know additional secrets and has taunted Red: ‚ÄúYou have no idea who I am or why I want the truth. Aren&#8217;t you curious? Don&#8217;t you have any questions?‚Äù Red‚Äôs response: ‚ÄúOh, I have plenty of questions, but none I&#8217;d pose to you. The answers will have to wait for me to find out on my own.‚Äù</p>
<p>Meanwhile, Liz has been reinstated as an agent by her therapist and fellow profiler Dr Sharon Fulton. Dr Fulton has disclosed to Liz that, on the side, she is a vigilante who recruits discredited agent-profilers to track down and kill serial killers according to their own M.O. Liz has offered to help her by giving her access to Red‚Äôs menagerie of ‚ÄúDoctors. Lawyers. Finders. Freaks. People with special skills.‚Äù
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ An affluent neighborhood ]<br />
[ Janis Ian&#8217;s ‚ô™ &#8220;At Seventeen&#8221; plays ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ I learned the truth at seventeen
</p></blockquote>
<p>Jerry Jawal: Reva, I&#8217;m home! Where are you? </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ That love was meant for beauty queens<br />
And high-school girls with clear-skinned smiles
</p></blockquote>
<p>Jerry: Reva?<br />
[ Reva is doing her homework ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Who married young and then retired
</p></blockquote>

<h3>‚≠ï Script 5:18 Zarak Mosadek (‚Ññ 23)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief: </b> Ian Garvey still has the duffel bag Red is looking for which contains a skeleton whose identity Red wants to hide from Liz and the world. But now Red has a ledger containing information on the original source of the opium smuggled into the US by the Nash Syndicate which Garvey protects and which is the source of his power. Red plans to use it as leverage to get back the skeleton. Meanwhile Garvey has learned that Liz is important to Red in addition to being a witness to his murder of Tom. Garvey has claimed to Red that he himself wants to know the ‚Äúwhole truth‚Äù regarding the skeleton whose identity he learned when Tom and Nick Korpal looked it up on a classified database using Liz‚Äôs credentials (unbeknownst to her). Garvey taunted Red asking him if he wasn‚Äôt curious about why he (Garvey) would be interested. Red said he wanted to learn the ‚Äúwhole truth‚Äù on his own, not through Garvey. Liz and the Task Force know Red is looking for the duffel bag, but not what is in it or why he wants to keep it secret. Red has flown Tony Mejia, a material witness to another murder committed by Garvey (that of Detective Norman Singleton, who was investigating Tom‚Äôs murder) out of the country to keep Tony from testifying until he gets the duffel back ‚Äì and to keep him away from Garvey, who would kill him. Red has told Garvey that once he gets the skeleton back, he will kill Garvey. Liz wants Red to get his duffel back if only to get him to return Tony Mejia who will corroborate her own testimony that Garvey is a dirty cop and a murderer.
</p></blockquote>

<h3>‚≠ï Script 5:19 Ian Garvey (‚Ññ 13) ‚Äì Conclusion</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief: </b> Red has succeeded in earning the gratitude of Ian Garvey‚Äôs opium supplier, Zarak Mosadek, by rescuing his son from the Taliban, a Paris operation he accomplished with help from the FBI. Cooper approved the operation over the objection of Cynthia Panabaker of the CIA which had recently cut ties to Mosadek as an informant. In gratitude to Red, Mosadek will meet with Ian Garvey in the U.S. to give him the bad news that his opium supply is at risk ‚Äì the source of Garvey‚Äôs power within the Nash Drug Syndicate. Red plans to use his leverage to retrieve from Garvey the duffel bag full of bones whose identity Red wants to keep a secret from Liz and the world. He has also vowed to Garvey that he will kill him once he gets the bones back. </p>
<p>In Red‚Äôs absense, Liz has worked with Aram to track Garvey, who killed both Tom and the detective investigating Tom‚Äôs murder, Norman Singleton. She and Aram followed Garvey 50 miles to Baltimore where they saw Garvey embrace a woman on the sidewalk in front of a bar, Pete‚Äôs Tavern. Aram identified the woman as Lillian May Roth, 35 years old, an employee of the bar. Later, Liz confronted Lillian and compelled her to come to her apartment and demanded information on Garvey. Lillian explained that Garvey was a surrogate father to her and  got her into witness protection years ago to protect her from her real father, a career criminal on the FBI‚Äôs Most Wanted List ‚Äì Raymond Reddington! She is Red‚Äôs daughter Jennifer by Carla (aka Naomi Hyland). Liz confided to Lillian that she herself is the daughter of Raymond Reddington.
</p></blockquote>

<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Zarak Mosadek, opium supplier to the Nash Syndicate headed by Ian Garvey, walks in a park with Red; Dembe follows several steps behind ]<br />
Mosadek: Ian Garvey is‚Äì How do you Americans say it? A dead man walking? I cut him off. He no longer represents my interests in your country.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I trust he knows why and what he must do to regain your patronage?<br />

<b>Red:</b> Unhappiness motivates whimpering. Action is motivated by fear.<br />

<b>Red:</b> Then he&#8217;ll bring me what I need, and your debt will be paid.<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ DOORBELL RINGS, DOOR OPENS ] [ Liz enters a apartment ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> After more than two decades on your Most Wanted List, I&#8217;ve become something of an FBI buff. <b>Red:</b> To get our man and keep my privacy.<br />

<b>Red:</b> That is ridiculous.<br />

<b>Red:</b> I won&#8217;t tell you something that&#8217;s none of your business. It was none of Tom&#8217;s business. You may feel entitled to know what it is because he died trying to figure out what it was, but you&#8217;re not. A fact which I have patiently tried to get you to understand. Be hurt. Blame me. Howl at the moon for all I care. But this is my problem, not yours.</p>

<h3>‚≠ï Script 5:20 Nicholas T Moore (‚Ññ 110)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief: </b> Red made a deal with opium supplier Zarak Mosadek to have him cut his cartel‚Äôs supply to Ian Garvey‚Äôs Nash Syndicate unless Garvey gave Red the duffel bag containing a skeleton that Red is trying to keep from Liz. But Mosadek double-crossed Red, instructing Garvey to instead kill Red when he turned up to get the duffel bag. The FBI found out about the plot via a bug that Liz planted on Lilly (or Jennifer, Red‚Äôs other daughter and half-sister). Lilly confronted Garvey with the information about Garvey‚Äôs crimes that Liz had told her about and challenged him to deny them. She had known Garvey only as a ‚Äúgood man‚Äù who had saved her from Red and gotten her into witness protection. Ever since the Christmas Even when Red disappeared (12/24/1990), Garvey had acted as a surrogate father to Lilly. Garvey denied the crimes Liz told Lilly about (his drug connections and murdering Tom), but told her he planned to rid the world of Raymond Reddington at a meeting planned for the next day.</p>
<p>The FBI told Red about the double-cross and Red then pulled off a double-double-cross by turning his associate Tony Pagliaro into an exact replicate of Garvey (using the skills of Raleigh Sinclair, who can put a person in two places at once). The fake Garvey showed up to the meetup between Red and Mosadek and killed Mosadek. Law enforcement ID‚Äôd the killer to the public as Garvey. Meanwhile, Red and Dembe had captured the real Garvey, but he caused a car crash and escaped, and headed to Pete‚Äôs Tavern, to get help fleeing law enforcement from Lilly. Liz headed there, too, and was arresting Garvey but he forestalled her saying he could tell her the story of what was in the duffel bag. That‚Äôs when Red ‚Äì using location info Aram provided from the bug ‚Äì showed up and threatened to kill Garvey if he uttered even ‚Äúone article‚Äù about the duffel bag. Liz then turned her gun on Red, insisting Garvey tell the story. Lilly got in-between Red and Garvey, begging Red to spare Garvey and telling Red she was Jennifer, his long-lost daughter. Red, though stunned, told Dembe to remove Jennifer from the line of fire. But Garvey pulled his gun and shot, hitting Red and wounding him. Liz then shot Garvey three times in the chest, wounds that appear to be fatal.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A little girl, Maybelle, SCREAMS. She is running through a woods in winter with her father. She trips and falls ]<br />

[ Robert runs ahead BREATHING HEAVILY ]<br />
[ Maybelle pours powder from the jar around her in a circle then applies two streaks of the powder to her own forehead ]</p>

<p>&nbsp;<br />
Dr Woerner: When I met Frost, it was as if he&#8217;d come from another time. His knowledge of history, science, pop culture ‚Äì they all ceased in 1957, as if they&#8217;d been erased or simply never happened at all.<br />

Early in his treatment, we believed he might be enduring hypnagogic hallucinations, but in the end, there was no clearer explanation other than what Frost believed to be real was real, that he&#8217;d somehow survived a cataclysmic event he called The Age of Contagion.<br />
[ KNOCK ON DOOR ]<br />
Woman: Found it.<br />
Dr Woerner: Perhaps it would be best if you heard it from Frost himself.</p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>[ On Recording: ]</b><br />
Dr Woerner: Tell me again when it happened.<br />
WP Frost: June 24, 1957.<br />
Dr Woerner: And what happened on that day? How did it get out of control?<br />
Frost: Carl Davies. He was a tech at a medical research lab called Cyntax. Suffered an accidental needle stick. Within six hours, they&#8217;d lost containment of Cambridge. England was infected by the next night, America three days later.<br />
Dr Woerner: But you ‚Äì you got out?<br />
Frost: Not me, the elders. They made it into the woods. Only survived because there was a wretched freeze, killed most of &#8217;em, but a few of the uninfected survived.<br />
Dr Woerner: Those survivors who went on to found New Haven, they remain isolated? Free from infection by the‚Äì What do you call them?<br />
Frost: The Ollo.<br />
Dr Woerner: Remind me, who are the Ollo?<br />
Frost: The others. Like you. The ones who carry the strain. That&#8217;s why we guard New Haven, keep it pure.<br />
Dr Woerner: What happens if someone wanders away or gets infected?<br />
Frost: Gotta get purified, set clean, taken to the inglenook.
</p></blockquote>

Moore: Back away now, or I swear I&#8217;ll shoot you myself.<br />

Moore: I don&#8217;t know who that is.<br />

Aram: Is she hurt? Just- Could- Could you- Could you just tell me if she&#8217;s okay?<br />
Kit: You heard Mr Moore. Back away. Do it now!<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 5:21 Lawrence Dane Devlin (‚Ññ 26)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief: </b> As Dickens might have said, ‚ÄòIan Garvey is dead as a door-mail.‚Äô So is Red‚Äôs ex, Naomi Hyland. Red asked Lilly (Red‚Äôs daughter, born Jennifer, who now goes by the name Lillian May Roth) to take him to see Naomi. Lilly said she first had some questions for Red, particularly, why he abandoned her and her mother on Christmas Eve in 1990. Red replied that he had had to cut ties to keep his enemies away from them. </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Red:</b> In 1990, the KGB and the CIA had almost nothing in common except the mutual determination to hunt down one individual.<br />
Lilly: You.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Being a fugitive from American law enforcement is a lot easier than being a fugitive from the two most powerful nations on Earth. And anyone close to a target of theirs becomes a target themselves.
</p></blockquote>
<p>The reason both the KGB And CIA were hunting him, Red said, was that he had discovered The Cabal, the insidious international secret organization he had ‚Äústumbled across and tried to destroy. To prevent that, they tried to destroy me.‚Äù </p>
<p>After their discussion, Lilly took Red to see her mother ‚Äì in a cemetery. Naomi was shot and killed leaving her apartment in 2017. Lilly asked Red to never contact her again. Red agreed.</p>
<p>Red had hoped Naomi might be able to help him locate the duffel bag containing a skeleton that he is desperately trying to locate before Liz does. At least half a dozen people have already died over this pursuit, including Tom, Liz‚Äôs husband. Red‚Äôs remaining lead is an associate of Ian Garvey‚Äôs, a young man named Judson, who has told Red that Garvey took the duffel bag on a flight to Costa Rica and came back without it. Red and Dembe were about to fly in Red‚Äôs jet to Costa Rica when Liz showed up. She quickly surmised the reason behind the planned trip. But she also has an urgent reason for intervening ‚Äì Samar has been abducted and Red‚Äôs help is deemed critical to locating her.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<b>Voiceover:</b> Previously on &#8220;The Blacklist&#8221;:<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />

Devlin: Yeah. [ CLEARS THROAT ] [ EXHALES DEEPLY ] Mm. The taking of a life, I&#8217;ve only done it a few times, and I take no pleasure in it. Once you&#8217;re gone, we&#8217;ll make it right. Send you back to the earth ‚Äì the way God intended.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Post Office ] [ Nicholas T Moore, the cult leader, is now in custody and is being interrogated by Cooper. Cooper shows Moore images of Devlin from a surveillance camera ]<br />
Cooper: I want a name.<br />
Moore: I don&#8217;t know who that is.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />

Liz: You mean people?<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Cooper: [ To Moore ] How&#8217;s it work? Someone stumbles upon your little utopia, becomes a threat, and what ‚Äì this man kills them? Gets rid of them?<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Kit: If this guy does exist, I never met him. Only Moore would know his name, anyway.<br />
Ressler: Do you actually think that he may talk?<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Moore: What if I could remember this man&#8217;s name and help you find your missing agent? Would you let me walk away?<br />
Cooper: And why would we agree to that?<br />
Moore: Because I&#8217;m giving you a chance to save this young woman&#8217;s life ‚Äì trade my life for hers. All you have to do is let me go ‚Äì you get her back.<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 5:22 Sutton Ross (‚Ññ 17)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief: </b> Aram and Samar are ‚Äú‚ô´ At Last‚Äù engaged. Never mind that she said ‚ÄúYes‚Äù before he proposed, the serious problem they face now is she is in a coma after nearly drowning in a submerged van before Aram rescued her. Time will tell if she will wake up or ever be able to breathe on her own again.</p>
<p>Speaking of time, Red and Liz are in the final sprint to recover the duffel bag containing a skeleton that Mr Kaplan intended to be delivered to Liz but Tom intercepted and was killed for his trouble. Both Red and Liz know who has the duffel bag, though Red knows the true identity of the man who has it (Sutton Ross) and Liz only has a pseudonym (Max Birmingham). US Marshall and dirty cop Ian Garvey, who killed Tom for the duffel bag to wield power over Red, managed to deliver it to Ross before he himself was killed by Liz in a showdown between Garvey and Red that got out of hand. Sutton Ross is an enemy of Red‚Äôs who Garvey had ‚Äúdisappeared‚Äù into Witness Protection and who Red had thought was dead. </p>
<p>Liz has no idea what is in the duffel bag, and Red intends to keep it that way. Liz believes the duffel contains a secret of Red‚Äôs that Mr Kaplan wanted her to know. But, given the choice between going with Kaplan or staying with Red, in last year‚Äôs Finale, Liz chose Red, an act that resulted in a series of events ending in Mr Kaplan‚Äôs suicide. If Liz had learned the secret, would she have chosen differently? The yearlong quest will come to a climax in this Season Finale.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ ‚ô™ Heavy Metal music playing ] [ Men dressed in FBI uniforms, led by Sutton Ross, enter the offices of Veritable Robotics in Richmond VA ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Open road, follow me<br />

<p>Sutton Ross: Walter Reardon?<br />
Reardon: Who are you?<br />
Ross: I&#8217;m Special Agent Vernon Duquesne, FBI. You&#8217;re under arrest. [ To his men ] Take everything! Internal audits, SEC filings, corporate minutes. I want it all vouchered as evidence.<br />
Reardon: Evidence of what?<br />
Ross: Market manipulation in violation of U.S. Code 7 Section 13 wire fraud, money laundering. You and your lawyer have all the time in the world to read the indictment before the arraignment.<br />
Holt Campbell: His lawyer&#8217;s right here. Holt Campbell. Veritable&#8217;s general counsel. You want to tell me what the hell is going on?<br />
[ Ross hands him papers ]<br />
Ross: Arrest and search warrants signed by the U.S. Duty Magistrate.<br />
Campbell: Where&#8217;s the affidavits in support of the warrants?<br />
Ross: Sealed.<br />
[ The men push past with boxes ]<br />
Campbell: Those documents contain trade secrets we&#8217;ve spent millions to acquire and protect.<br />
[ DIALING ] Call Judge Kerr&#8217;s chambers. Get his clerk on the line. This is Holt Campbell at Veritable Robotics. Well, you should know the name. Your boss signed warrants to search our offices and arrest our CFO. Really? Well, if he didn&#8217;t sign them, why am I holding the paperwork? </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ TIRES SCREECHING ]<br />
[ Campbell rushes out onto a loading dock. Walter Reardon is cuffed to a pole. Bankers boxes are stacked nearby ]<br />

Campbell: What happened?<br />
Reardon: Nothing. Whoever they were, they left everything behind. I want to know why.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The hospital where Samar is being treated. She is unconscious, hooked up to a ventilator ]<br />
[ MONITOR BEEPING RHYTHMICALLY ] [ VENTILATOR HISSES ] [ WOMAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY ON P.A. ]<br />
Nurse: What are you doing?<br />
Aram: She&#8217;s shivering.<br />
Nurse: She&#8217;s supposed to be cold.<br />
Aram: I know. I read up on TTM, how you circulate cold saline through her femoral artery, but her core body temperate was only 91 degrees.<br />
Nurse: She is suffering from cerebral ischemia. Cooling her protects her brain while she heals.<br />
Aram: Right. By decreasing the brain&#8217;s demand for oxygen, you reduce neurotransmitter production like glutamate.<br />
Nurse: Lovely. Looks like someone&#8217;s been reading up on Wikipedia.<br />
Aram: I read the page and the footnotes. 91 degrees was an AHA guideline in 2010, but in 2015, the journal <i>Resuscitation</i> concluded that 97 degrees was more effective.<br />
Nurse: I&#8217;m just following protocol. Are you her husband? Part of our medical directive?<br />
Aram: I&#8217;m her fianc√©. Granted, I proposed while she was unconscious.<br />
Nurse: Do you have power of attorney?<br />
Aram: No, but‚Äì<br />
Nurse: Then I&#8217;m gonna have to ask you to step aside.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Cooper‚Äôs office ]<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m ashamed of this.<br />
Cooper: You shouldn&#8217;t be.<br />

Cooper: What do you know about the man?<br />
Liz: Well, for starters, I know his real name isn&#8217;t Max Birmingham.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz briefs the Task Force ]<br />
Liz: The man we&#8217;re looking for is Sutton Ross. In the &#8217;80s, when a company or a country wanted to steal R&amp;D rather than develop it, Ross and his team stole it for them.<br />
Ressler: Didn&#8217;t he steal R&amp;D on a stealth fighter for China?<br />
Liz: A defective stealth fighter called the Grayscape Seventeen. The Navy knew Ross was working for China, so they made sure he stole plans for a plane that couldn&#8217;t fly, and when it crashed, China blamed Ross, turned him over to the feds, who issued an arrest warrant, and Ross disappeared.<br />
Cooper: Until showing up in Costa Rica under the alias &#8220;Max Birmingham.&#8221;<br />
Ressler: So, why would Garvey give him the bag?<br />
Liz: Because when Ross went AWOL, Garvey was the Marshal assigned to arrest him, and instead of bringing him in, Garvey ended up protecting him.<br />
Ressler: Yeah, but these two haven&#8217;t met in weeks. Any idea where Ross is now?<br />
Liz: Yes. Doing business, as usual. Ross and a dozen suspects posing as FBI agents showed up to a robotics company yesterday, waving phony warrants.<br />
Cooper: So the guy holding Reddington&#8217;s secret is stealing tech from a robotics company?<br />
Liz: Yes and no. The police report says he stole it, and then left it all behind.<br />
Cooper: Nobody robs a company for kicks. Get there. If we find out what he was really after, we&#8217;ll find him and the bag before Reddington.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />

[ CHUCKLES ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Veritable Robotics ]<br />
Campbell: Every document taken from Reardon&#8217;s office was returned.<br />

Campbell: Not just the office. This very corridor. Walter&#8217;s office is across the hall from one of our research specialists, Ravi Desai. Three of the hard drives are missing. They contain Ravi&#8217;s personal research on something called the Rafferty Project.<br />
Liz: Have you spoken to Mr. Desai?<br />
Campbell: We&#8217;ve called and left messages, but we haven&#8217;t been able to reach him. His kids are off from school, so he took vacation time.<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Aram is seated next to Samar‚Äôs hospital bed working on a laptop ]<br />

Liz: Thank us? We feel awful for imposing.<br />

Aram: Well, the backup files indicate that it&#8217;s some kind of exoskeleton, a manned robot designed to help people go into hazardous areas.<br />
Ressler: That&#8217;s an idea that Ross could sell for a fortune on the open market.<br />
Aram: Well, maybe, but the idea is all he&#8217;d be selling. Whoever buys these drives will not be able to build one.<br />
Ressler: Why not?<br />
Aram: Well, the files are all snippets of ideas and partial equations. I mean, Desai could build a robot from them, but no one else could, not without him to explain what they mean.<br />
Ressler: Well, we need to get to Desai and lock him down before Ross grabs him.<br />
Aram: Oh, well, that shouldn&#8217;t be hard. He&#8217;s at a matinee with his kids.<br />
Liz: How do you know that?<br />
Aram: Like I said, I follow him on Instagram, and he just posted a picture with them on his way to a show at the Kittredge Theater.</p>

var WPGroHo = {"my_hash":""};
</script>
<script type='text/javascript' src='https://s0.wp.com/wp-content/mu-plugins/gravatar-hovercards/wpgroho.js?m=1380573781h'></script>

	<script>
		//initialize and attach hovercards to all gravatars
		jQuery( document ).ready( function( $ ) {

			if (typeof Gravatar === "undefined"){
				return;
			}

			if ( typeof Gravatar.init !== "function" ) {
				return;
			}			

			Gravatar.profile_cb = function( hash, id ) {
				WPGroHo.syncProfileData( hash, id );
			};
			Gravatar.my_hash = WPGroHo.my_hash;
			Gravatar.init( 'body', '#wp-admin-bar-my-account' );
		});
	</script>

		<div style="display:none">
	</div>
